2033
02:23:47,399 --> 02:23:56,330
Charles X, who had become king in 1824, believed
that he had total power over the French people.

2034
02:23:56,330 --> 02:24:01,569
He was a strong supporter of the Catholic
church and the aristocracy, and he took away

2035
02:24:01,569 --> 02:24:06,870
the freedoms that Napoleon had given the ordinary
citizens.

2036
02:24:06,870 --> 02:24:12,279
Although this made him very unpopular, he
thought that his opponents would be too weak

2037
02:24:12,279 --> 02:24:15,399
to prevent him from doing what he wanted.

2038
02:24:15,399 --> 02:24:17,340
He was wrong.

2039
02:24:17,340 --> 02:24:23,690
In 1830, there was a peaceful revolution,
and he was forced to leave.

2040
02:24:23,690 --> 02:24:30,460
The new king, Louis-Philippe, was a brave
and clever man who loved his country.

2041
02:24:30,460 --> 02:24:35,540
The ordinary people liked him at first, but
he soon showed that he was more interested

2042
02:24:35,540 --> 02:24:40,590
in power for his family than democracy for
his people.

2043
02:24:40,590 --> 02:24:46,610
He understood business, but he could not understand
the problems of poor people.

2044
02:24:46,610 --> 02:24:52,650
Neither could he understand the concept of
freedom of speech, and he often sent soldiers

2045
02:24:52,650 --> 02:24:58,740
into the streets to attack people who were
making public protests.

2046
02:24:58,740 --> 02:25:05,300
As the summer approached, the mood of the
workers and the poor became angrier and angrier.

2047
02:25:05,300 --> 02:25:14,000
Their anger exploded into violence in June
1832, when General Lamarque died.

2048
02:25:14,000 --> 02:25:20,521
The General had been very popular with the
people of France because of his love for Napoleon.

2049
02:25:20,521 --> 02:25:26,980
The day of his funeral was arranged for 5
June, and thousands of people saw this as

2050
02:25:26,980 --> 02:25:32,021
a chance to make a public protest against
the king and his government.

2051
02:25:32,021 --> 02:25:36,510
At first, the funeral went quietly.

2052
02:25:36,510 --> 02:25:40,870
Soldiers accompanied the coffin as it was
carried slowly across Paris.

2053
02:25:40,870 --> 02:25:47,850
A large crowd followed behind, waving flags
and carrying swords and heavy sticks.

2054
02:25:47,850 --> 02:25:53,830
The crowd grew more and more excited, until
finally they tried to take the coffin away

2055
02:25:53,830 --> 02:25:57,090
from the soldiers and carry it across a bridge.

2056
02:25:57,090 --> 02:26:02,080
Their exit was blocked by more soldiers on
horseback.

2057
02:26:02,080 --> 02:26:04,240
For a moment, nothing happened.

2058
02:26:04,240 --> 02:26:07,690
Then there were two gunshots.

2059
02:26:07,690 --> 02:26:13,350
The first shot killed the commander of the
soldiers guarding the exit to the bridge.

2060
02:26:13,350 --> 02:26:18,860
The second killed a deaf old woman who was
trying to shut her window.

2061
02:26:18,860 --> 02:26:22,180
Then the fighting started.

2062
02:26:22,180 --> 02:26:27,410
Soldiers attacked the crowd with swords; the
crowd threw stones and ran screaming across

2063
02:26:27,410 --> 02:26:29,200
the bridge.

2064
02:26:29,200 --> 02:26:37,140
Minutes later, the sounds of war echoed across
the whole city of Paris.

2065
02:26:37,140 --> 02:26:38,140
***

2066
02:26:38,140 --> 02:26:42,340
As soon as the fighting started, Enjolras
and several of his friends started to build

2067
02:26:42,340 --> 02:26:49,580
a barricade outside the Corinth wine shop
in the rue de la Chanvrerie, a small street

2068
02:26:49,580 --> 02:26:54,460
surrounded by dark alleys in the market district
of Paris.

2069
02:26:54,460 --> 02:27:00,240
Enjolras had been joined by many strangers
as he and his friends had run shouting along

2070
02:27:00,240 --> 02:27:02,070
the street.

2071
02:27:02,070 --> 02:27:08,870
There was a tall, grey-haired man whom nobody
knew, but whose strong, brave face had impressed

2072
02:27:08,870 --> 02:27:09,910
everybody.

2073
02:27:09,910 --> 02:27:16,070
There were several street children, excited
by the sound of battle, who also joined them.

2074
02:27:16,070 --> 02:27:21,770
One of these children was Eponine, who had
dressed like a boy so that no one would tell

2075
02:27:21,770 --> 02:27:24,380
her to go home.

2076
02:27:24,380 --> 02:27:29,240
Having run to tell Marius that his friends
were waiting for him, she was helping Enjolras

2077
02:27:29,240 --> 02:27:33,350
and his companions to build the barricade.

2078
02:27:33,350 --> 02:27:38,120
New people arrived all the time, bringing
with them gunpowder and weapons to fight the

2079
02:27:38,120 --> 02:27:41,650
soldiers who would be arriving very soon.

2080
02:27:41,650 --> 02:27:47,240
Enjolras, who was the leader of the rebels,
organized the building of a second barricade

2081
02:27:47,240 --> 02:27:51,810
and the manufacture of bullets from melted
silver.

2082
02:27:51,810 --> 02:27:57,510
The tall, grey-haired man was doing useful
work on the larger barricade, and Eponine

2083
02:27:57,510 --> 02:28:02,320
(whom everyone thought was a boy) worked hard
too.

2084
02:28:02,320 --> 02:28:07,641
The barricades were finished in less than
an hour and, with the sound of drums in the

2085
02:28:07,641 --> 02:28:13,980
city growing louder, Enjolras brought a table
out into the street and sat down with his

2086
02:28:13,980 --> 02:28:16,450
friends for a drink.

2087
02:28:16,450 --> 02:28:19,641
Night fell, but nothing happened.

2088
02:28:19,641 --> 02:28:24,870
While the fifty men behind the barricade waited
impatiently for the arrival of sixty thousand

2089
02:28:24,870 --> 02:28:29,920
soldiers, Enjolras approached the tall, grey-haired
man.

2090
02:28:29,920 --> 02:28:34,040
'Who are you?' he asked.

2091
02:28:34,040 --> 02:28:38,230
When the man said nothing, Enjolras became
suspicious.

2092
02:28:38,230 --> 02:28:42,790
'You're a policeman, aren't you?' he said.

2093
02:28:42,790 --> 02:28:47,090
The man smiled and eventually admitted that
he was.

2094
02:28:47,090 --> 02:28:52,540
'My name's Javert,' he said.

2095
02:28:52,540 --> 02:28:57,710
Before he could move, Enjolras ordered four
men to search him.

2096
02:28:57,710 --> 02:29:02,660
When they found a letter in his pocket which
proved that he had been sent to spy on them,

2097
02:29:02,660 --> 02:29:07,660
they tied him to a post inside the inn,

2098
02:29:07,660 --> 02:29:16,170
'You'll be shot two minutes before the barricade
falls,' Enjolras informed him.

2099
02:29:16,170 --> 02:29:17,170
***

2100
02:29:17,170 --> 02:29:22,062
Marius left the garden and, mad with grief
at losing Cosette, walked towards the sound

2101
02:29:22,062 --> 02:29:25,790
of drums and gunfire in the centre of the
city.

2102
02:29:25,790 --> 02:29:31,279
He had only one thought in his mind: he wanted
to die.

2103
02:29:31,279 --> 02:29:35,351
Marius pushed his way through the crowds of
frightened, murmuring people that filled the

2104
02:29:35,351 --> 02:29:38,710
streets until he reached the market area.

2105
02:29:38,710 --> 02:29:44,260
Here, he found the unlit streets suddenly
filled with soldiers.

2106
02:29:44,260 --> 02:29:50,510
Unafraid, Marius ran through the shadows,
ignoring shouts for him to stop.

2107
02:29:50,510 --> 02:29:57,370
Someone fired a gun and a bullet hit a wall
just behind him, but he didn't care.

2108
02:29:57,370 --> 02:30:02,970
He was just approaching the rue de Chanvrerie
when he heard a loud voice calling from the

2109
02:30:02,970 --> 02:30:06,830
shadows: 'Who's there?'

2110
02:30:06,830 --> 02:30:16,990
'The French Revolution!' he heard a distant
voice reply - the voice of his friend, Enjolras.

2111
02:30:16,990 --> 02:30:21,150
Marius stood behind an alley wall, hidden
in the shadows.

2112
02:30:21,150 --> 02:30:26,540
Around the corner, he could see a row of soldiers
aiming their guns down the rue de Chanvrerie,

2113
02:30:26,540 --> 02:30:28,090
waiting for the order to fire.

2114
02:30:28,090 --> 02:30:29,090
'Fire!'

2115
02:30:29,090 --> 02:30:32,330
the order finally came.

2116
02:30:32,330 --> 02:30:37,470
The street was lit with a sudden flash of
light and filled with the thunder of gunfire.

2117
02:30:37,470 --> 02:30:41,410
Then the soldiers attacked.

2118
02:30:41,410 --> 02:30:46,280
Marius stood up and ran along a series of
alleys that led into the rue de la Chanvrerie,

2119
02:30:46,280 --> 02:30:49,370
behind the Corinth wine shop.

2120
02:30:49,370 --> 02:30:54,260
When he reached the stronghold, soldiers were
already climbing the barricade, shooting at

2121
02:30:54,260 --> 02:30:55,870
the rebels.

2122
02:30:55,870 --> 02:31:02,120
Marius saw a soldier attacking Enjolras, who
had fallen backwards and was calling for help.

2123
02:31:02,120 --> 02:31:08,870
Marius took Javert's guns from his pockets
and shot the soldier dead.

2124
02:31:08,870 --> 02:31:13,450
Soldiers now occupied the top of the barricade,
but were unable to advance any further because

2125
02:31:13,450 --> 02:31:15,760
the defenders fought so fiercely.

2126
02:31:15,760 --> 02:31:21,620
Marius, who had thrown away his guns and was
now without a weapon, began to move towards

2127
02:31:21,620 --> 02:31:26,521
a barrel of gunpowder he had seen near the
door of the wine shop.

2128
02:31:26,521 --> 02:31:30,660
He did not notice a soldier aiming his gun
at him.

2129
02:31:30,660 --> 02:31:36,950
Neither did he see, at the moment the soldier
fired, a young boy dressed in rags jump in

2130
02:31:36,950 --> 02:31:43,740
front of the gun and fall wounded as the bullet
meant for Marius hit him in the hand.

2131
02:31:43,740 --> 02:31:46,870
'Put down your weapons and surrender!'

2132
02:31:46,870 --> 02:31:49,630
a soldier called from the top of the barricade.

2133
02:31:49,630 --> 02:31:50,689
'Fire!'

2134
02:31:50,689 --> 02:31:52,820
Enjolras shouted.

2135
02:31:52,820 --> 02:31:57,510
The soldiers and the rebels fired at each
other at the same time, filling the air with

2136
02:31:57,510 --> 02:32:00,220
thick clouds of dark smoke.

2137
02:32:00,220 --> 02:32:05,181
When the smoke cleared, there were many dead
bodies on both sides.

2138
02:32:05,181 --> 02:32:12,069
The survivors were reloading their guns in
silence, when suddenly a loud voice called,

2139
02:32:12,069 --> 02:32:17,710
'Get out now, or I'll blow up the barricade!'

2140
02:32:17,710 --> 02:32:22,030
All heads turned to stare in the direction
of the voice.

2141
02:32:22,030 --> 02:32:26,720
Marius was standing at the foot of the barricade,
holding a flaming torch above a barrel of

2142
02:32:26,720 --> 02:32:27,720
gunpowder.

2143
02:32:27,720 --> 02:32:36,420
'If you blow up the barricade,' a sergeant
called, 'you'll blow up yourself as well!'

2144
02:32:36,420 --> 02:32:41,300
Marius smiled and lowered the torch towards
the gunpowder.

2145
02:32:41,300 --> 02:32:46,050
Within seconds, the soldiers had left the
barricade, leaving their dead and wounded

2146
02:32:46,050 --> 02:32:50,720
behind, and were running into the darkness
at the far end of the street.

2147
02:32:50,720 --> 02:32:54,790
Enjolras threw his arms around Marius's neck.

2148
02:32:54,790 --> 02:32:58,080
'So you've come!' he cried.

2149
02:32:58,080 --> 02:33:04,160
Marius hugged Enjolras and many other friends
he recognized.

2150
02:33:04,160 --> 02:33:08,750
While the soldiers waited at the far end of
the street for further orders, and the rebels

2151
02:33:08,750 --> 02:33:14,359
removed dead bodies from the barricade and
took care of the wounded, Marius walked around

2152
02:33:14,359 --> 02:33:17,870
the stronghold in a kind of dream.

2153
02:33:17,870 --> 02:33:23,420
After two months of happiness with Cosette,
he was now in the middle of a war.

2154
02:33:23,420 --> 02:33:26,689
He could not believe this was happening to
him.

2155
02:33:26,689 --> 02:33:33,150
He was so confused that he did not recognize
Javert, tied to a post inside the inn throughout

2156
02:33:33,150 --> 02:33:35,220
the battle.

2157
02:33:35,220 --> 02:33:40,550
As he was walking by the smaller barricade,
his thoughts were interrupted by a weak voice

2158
02:33:40,550 --> 02:33:43,330
calling his name from the shadows.

2159
02:33:43,330 --> 02:33:46,439
'M. Marius!'

2160
02:33:46,439 --> 02:33:51,870
He looked about him but, seeing no one, he
started to walk away, thinking that he was

2161
02:33:51,870 --> 02:33:54,120
imagining things.

2162
02:33:54,120 --> 02:33:56,840
'M. Marius!'

2163
02:33:56,840 --> 02:33:59,470
He heard the voice again.

2164
02:33:59,470 --> 02:34:02,740
Marius gazed into the shadows, but could still
see nothing.

2165
02:34:02,740 --> 02:34:08,760
'I'm at your feet,' the voice said.

2166
02:34:08,760 --> 02:34:14,960
Looking down, Marius saw a dark shape crawling
along the ground towards him.

2167
02:34:14,960 --> 02:34:20,630
By the light of a lamp on the pavement, he
could see a torn jacket, trousers with holes

2168
02:34:20,630 --> 02:34:24,660
in them, and two bare feet.

2169
02:34:24,660 --> 02:34:32,080
A white face was turned towards him and the
voice asked, 'Do you recognize me?

2170
02:34:32,080 --> 02:34:34,930
It's Eponine.'

2171
02:34:34,930 --> 02:34:40,100
Marius bent down quickly, and saw that it
was indeed that unhappy girl, dressed in a

2172
02:34:40,100 --> 02:34:41,100
man's clothes.

2173
02:34:41,100 --> 02:34:45,080
'What are you doing here?' he said.

2174
02:34:45,080 --> 02:34:50,510
Then, noticing the pool of blood on the ground
behind her, cried, 'You're wounded!

2175
02:34:50,510 --> 02:34:52,149
I'll carry you to the inn.

2176
02:34:52,149 --> 02:34:54,229
They'll take care of you there.

2177
02:34:54,229 --> 02:34:56,439
Is it very bad?'

2178
02:34:56,439 --> 02:34:59,819
She showed him the bullet hole in her hand.

2179
02:34:59,819 --> 02:35:07,600
'A soldier was going to shoot you,' she said,
her voice no more than a whisper.

2180
02:35:07,600 --> 02:35:12,290
'But I put my hand in front of his gun.'

2181
02:35:12,290 --> 02:35:16,070
'You poor child,' Marius said.

2182
02:35:16,070 --> 02:35:19,320
'We'll put a bandage on that wound immediately.

2183
02:35:19,320 --> 02:35:20,320
You'll be all right.'

2184
02:35:20,320 --> 02:35:32,279
'The bullet passed through my hand,' Eponine
murmured, 'but it came out through my back.

2185
02:35:32,279 --> 02:35:40,220
It's no use trying to move me, but I'll tell
you how you can treat my wound better than

2186
02:35:40,220 --> 02:35:42,820
any doctor.

2187
02:35:42,820 --> 02:35:48,689
Sit down on that stone, close beside me.'

2188
02:35:48,689 --> 02:35:50,410
Marius sat next to her.

2189
02:35:50,410 --> 02:35:58,240
She rested her head on his knee and said without
looking at him, 'Oh, what happiness.

2190
02:35:58,240 --> 02:36:02,450
Now I don't feel any pain,'

2191
02:36:02,450 --> 02:36:04,649
For a moment she was silent.

2192
02:36:04,649 --> 02:36:09,900
She pressed her hand to her chest, from which
blood was pouring like dark wine.

2193
02:36:09,900 --> 02:36:15,600
Then, with a great effort, she raised herself
on one arm and, struggling for breath, looked

2194
02:36:15,600 --> 02:36:17,850
into Marius's eyes.

2195
02:36:17,850 --> 02:36:22,811
'I can't cheat you,' she said at last.

2196
02:36:22,811 --> 02:36:27,200
'I have a letter for you in my pocket.

2197
02:36:27,200 --> 02:36:30,450
I've had it since yesterday.

2198
02:36:30,450 --> 02:36:34,090
I was asked to post it, but I didn't.

2199
02:36:34,090 --> 02:36:37,240
I didn't want you to get it.

2200
02:36:37,240 --> 02:36:43,189
But now we're both going to die, it doesn't
matter, does it?

2201
02:36:43,189 --> 02:36:47,420
I can't be jealous any more.

2202
02:36:47,420 --> 02:36:50,860
Take your letter.'

2203
02:36:50,860 --> 02:36:56,590
She took hold of Marius's hand with her wounded
hand and, without seeming to feel the pain,

2204
02:36:56,590 --> 02:37:01,590
guided it to her pocket, from which he took
the letter.

2205
02:37:01,590 --> 02:37:08,470
'Now you must promise me something for my
trouble,' she said.

2206
02:37:08,470 --> 02:37:15,279
'You must kiss me on the forehead after I'm
dead...

2207
02:37:15,279 --> 02:37:16,760
I shall know.'

2208
02:37:16,760 --> 02:37:21,000
She let her head fall back on his knees.

2209
02:37:21,000 --> 02:37:26,550
Her eyelids trembled, and then she was still.

2210
02:37:26,550 --> 02:37:32,300
Just as Marius thought that her sad soul had
finally left her body, she slowly opened her

2211
02:37:32,300 --> 02:37:39,450
eyes, and said in a voice so sweet that it
seemed already to come from another world,

2212
02:37:39,450 --> 02:37:49,080
'You know, M. Marius, I think I was a little
bit in love with you.'

2213
02:37:49,080 --> 02:37:56,240
With those words, she closed her eyes for
the last time and died.

2214
02:37:56,240 --> 02:38:02,540
Marius kissed her pale forehead and laid her
gently on the ground.

2215
02:38:02,540 --> 02:38:08,330
Then he returned to the wine shop, and opened
the letter that she had given him.

2216
02:38:08,330 --> 02:38:11,080
By candlelight he read,

2217
02:38:11,080 --> 02:38:16,580
My dearest, We are leaving this house at once.

2218
02:38:16,580 --> 02:38:25,460
We go tonight to Number 7, rue de l'Homme-Arme,
and in a week we shall be in England.

2219
02:38:25,460 --> 02:38:30,910
Cosette, 4 June.

2220
02:38:30,910 --> 02:38:34,250
Marius covered Cosette's letter with kisses.

2221
02:38:34,250 --> 02:38:36,740
So she still loved him!

2222
02:38:36,740 --> 02:38:44,080
He thought for a moment that now he must not
die, but then he thought, 'She's going away.'

2223
02:38:44,080 --> 02:38:48,480
She was going with her father to England,
and his grandfather had refused to give his

2224
02:38:48,480 --> 02:38:51,050
permission for him to marry.

2225
02:38:51,050 --> 02:38:57,420
Nothing had changed, and he decided that he
had one last duty to perform: he must send

2226
02:38:57,420 --> 02:39:02,080
Cosette a final message and tell her of his
death.

2227
02:39:02,080 --> 02:39:06,670
He tore a page out of the pocket notebook
he always carried and wrote:

2228
02:39:06,670 --> 02:39:10,410
Our marriage was impossible.

2229
02:39:10,410 --> 02:39:15,580
I went to my grandfather, and he refused to
give his permission.

2230
02:39:15,580 --> 02:39:19,550
I have no money, and neither have you.

2231
02:39:19,550 --> 02:39:23,990
I hurried to see you, but you had gone.

2232
02:39:23,990 --> 02:39:27,120
You remember the promise I made you.

2233
02:39:27,120 --> 02:39:29,250
I shall keep it.

2234
02:39:29,250 --> 02:39:30,780
I shall die.

2235
02:39:30,780 --> 02:39:33,979
I love you.

2236
02:39:33,979 --> 02:39:41,630
When you read this, my soul will be very near
and smiling at you.

2237
02:39:41,630 --> 02:39:46,520
He folded the letter, wrote Cosette's new
address on the back and called over a young

2238
02:39:46,520 --> 02:39:47,750
boy.

2239
02:39:47,750 --> 02:39:52,120
'What's your name?' he asked the boy.

2240
02:39:52,120 --> 02:39:53,420
'Gavroche.'

2241
02:39:53,420 --> 02:39:58,560
'Well, Gavroche, will you do something for
me?

2242
02:39:58,560 --> 02:40:04,521
I want you to deliver this letter to the address
written on the outside.'

2243
02:40:04,521 --> 02:40:10,550
The boy scratched his head, thought for a
moment, and then, with a sudden movement,

2244
02:40:10,550 --> 02:40:14,300
took the letter and ran off into the night.

2245
02:40:14,300 --> 02:40:16,700
CHAPTER ELEVEN

2246
02:40:16,700 --> 02:40:17,700
The Letter

2247
02:40:17,700 --> 02:40:26,660
Jean Valjean, at that moment, was in a state
of terrible shock.

2248
02:40:26,660 --> 02:40:31,529
For the first time in their life together,
he and Cosette had quarrelled.

2249
02:40:31,529 --> 02:40:37,330
She had not wanted to leave the house, but
she had eventually obeyed him.

2250
02:40:37,330 --> 02:40:42,960
They had left quickly, at nightfall, bringing
their servant, Toussaint, with them, but very

2251
02:40:42,960 --> 02:40:45,290
little luggage.

2252
02:40:45,290 --> 02:40:50,630
Cosette had brought her letter case and blotter
with her, Valjean his box of child's clothing

2253
02:40:50,630 --> 02:40:55,950
and the old National Guard uniform which all
respectable men possessed, and which he had

2254
02:40:55,950 --> 02:40:58,160
worn under a previous identity.

2255
02:40:58,160 --> 02:41:02,601
In their new house, they went to bed in silence.

2256
02:41:02,601 --> 02:41:08,760
Cosette, however, did not leave her bedroom
the next day, and Jean Valjean had dinner

2257
02:41:08,760 --> 02:41:10,430
alone.

2258
02:41:10,430 --> 02:41:15,340
As he was eating, Toussaint told him about
the fighting in the city, but he did not pay

2259
02:41:15,340 --> 02:41:16,971
much attention.

2260
02:41:16,971 --> 02:41:19,860
He was too worried about Cosette.

2261
02:41:19,860 --> 02:41:24,630
There was no reason, he thought, why they
should not continue to live happily together

2262
02:41:24,630 --> 02:41:25,630
in England.

2263
02:41:25,630 --> 02:41:32,020
As long as he had Cosette, he would be happy,
and it did not matter where they lived.

2264
02:41:32,020 --> 02:41:36,980
He began to feel happier as he thought about
the journey they would soon be making.

2265
02:41:36,980 --> 02:41:42,979
He stood up and was going to leave the room
when something made him stop.

2266
02:41:42,979 --> 02:41:45,990
He glanced again at the mirror.

2267
02:41:45,990 --> 02:41:51,649
Cosette's blotter was lying on a cupboard
just below it and, as Valjean stared at its

2268
02:41:51,649 --> 02:41:56,080
reflection, he read the following lines:

2269
02:41:56,080 --> 02:42:00,330
My dearest, We are leaving this house at once.

2270
02:42:00,330 --> 02:42:08,021
We go tonight to Number 7, rue de 1'Homme-Arme,
and in a week we shall be in England.

2271
02:42:08,021 --> 02:42:11,660
Cosette, 4June.

2272
02:42:11,660 --> 02:42:16,880
In her unhappy state of mind, Cosette had
forgotten to remove the page that she had

2273
02:42:16,880 --> 02:42:20,630
used to blot the letter she had written to
Marius.

2274
02:42:20,630 --> 02:42:27,090
She had left it on the cupboard and the mirror,
reflecting the backwards handwriting, made

2275
02:42:27,090 --> 02:42:31,460
the message clearly visible.

2276
02:42:31,460 --> 02:42:38,391
Valjean moved closer to the mirror and read
the lines again, not wanting to believe them.

2277
02:42:38,391 --> 02:42:42,870
But there was no doubt that this was Cosette's
handwriting.

2278
02:42:42,870 --> 02:42:49,300
He began to shake and he fell back into an
armchair, feeling angry and betrayed.

2279
02:42:49,300 --> 02:42:55,830
He had suffered terribly over the years and,
until now, he had survived every disaster.

2280
02:42:55,830 --> 02:43:01,290
But this was the worst thing that had ever
happened to him - someone was threatening

2281
02:43:01,290 --> 02:43:06,070
to rob him of the only person he loved!

2282
02:43:06,070 --> 02:43:13,899
He murmured to himself, 'She's going to leave
me,' and the pain of those words cut into

2283
02:43:13,899 --> 02:43:17,250
his heart like a knife.

2284
02:43:17,250 --> 02:43:21,460
After a short time, he rose to his feet and
looked again at the blotter.

2285
02:43:21,460 --> 02:43:28,910
His anger and misery of minutes before had
been replaced by a terrible calmness.

2286
02:43:28,910 --> 02:43:33,630
He stared at the blotter, coldness in his
eyes, the darkness of the deepest night in

2287
02:43:33,630 --> 02:43:34,780
his heart.

2288
02:43:34,780 --> 02:43:39,910
He remembered clearly the young man in the
Luxembourg Gardens who had shown such great

2289
02:43:39,910 --> 02:43:47,150
interest in Cosette, and he was certain that
this was the man she had written to.

2290
02:43:47,150 --> 02:43:51,729
He went out into the night and sat on the
doorstep, his heart filled with a terrible

2291
02:43:51,729 --> 02:43:57,170
hatred for the man who was trying to steal
Cosette from him.

2292
02:43:57,170 --> 02:44:03,061
He sat for a long time listening to the sound
of distant gunfire in the city, wondering

2293
02:44:03,061 --> 02:44:08,920
how to get his revenge, when suddenly he heard
footsteps.

2294
02:44:08,920 --> 02:44:15,180
Looking up, he saw a pale-faced boy, dressed
in rags, studying the numbers of the houses

2295
02:44:15,180 --> 02:44:17,960
in the street.

2296
02:44:17,960 --> 02:44:25,050
Seeing Valjean on his doorstep, the boy stopped
and asked, 'Do you live in this street?'

2297
02:44:25,050 --> 02:44:26,620
'Yes.

2298
02:44:26,620 --> 02:44:28,190
Why?'

2299
02:44:28,190 --> 02:44:30,229
'I'm looking for Number Seven.

2300
02:44:30,229 --> 02:44:32,890
I have a letter for a girl who lives here.'

2301
02:44:32,890 --> 02:44:35,910
'Well, I'm the girl's father.

2302
02:44:35,910 --> 02:44:37,800
You can give the letter to me.

2303
02:44:37,800 --> 02:44:44,680
Oh, and one more thing before you go,'Valjean
said when the boy had handed him the letter.

2304
02:44:44,680 --> 02:44:47,970
'Where should I take the reply?'

2305
02:44:47,970 --> 02:44:54,971
'That letter comes from the barricade in the
rue de la Chanvrerie,' the boy replied.

2306
02:44:54,971 --> 02:44:57,870
'Which is where I'm going now.

2307
02:44:57,870 --> 02:44:58,870
Goodnight citizen.'

2308
02:44:58,870 --> 02:45:05,200
Jean Valjean went back into the house and
tried to make sense of the words that danced

2309
02:45:05,200 --> 02:45:10,220
before his eyes: I shall die...

2310
02:45:10,220 --> 02:45:15,970
When you read this, my soul will be very near...

2311
02:45:15,970 --> 02:45:20,370
This was enough to fill his hate-filled heart
with sudden joy.

2312
02:45:20,370 --> 02:45:22,880
So, the problem was solved!

2313
02:45:22,880 --> 02:45:29,700
The man who threatened his happiness was going
to die - was perhaps already dead.

2314
02:45:29,700 --> 02:45:38,280
Then Valjean frowned and, after a quick calculation,
decided that Marius was probably still alive.

2315
02:45:38,280 --> 02:45:40,120
But it made no difference.

2316
02:45:40,120 --> 02:45:45,790
He was still certain to die, and Valjean's
happiness would be safe.

2317
02:45:45,790 --> 02:45:50,540
If he kept the letter in his pocket, Cosette
would never know what had happened to the

2318
02:45:50,540 --> 02:45:56,470
other man, and life with her would continue
the same as before.

2319
02:45:56,470 --> 02:45:58,740
What happiness!

2320
02:45:58,740 --> 02:46:05,721
But his happiness had no sooner returned than
it disappeared again in a cloud of despair.

2321
02:46:05,721 --> 02:46:08,960
In his heart he knew he had no choice.

2322
02:46:08,960 --> 02:46:13,399
For the sake of Cosette's happiness, he would
have to try and save the life of the man she

2323
02:46:13,399 --> 02:46:18,060
loved - the man he hated more than any other
in the world.

2324
02:46:18,060 --> 02:46:25,601
Half an hour later he left the house, dressed
in his National Guard uniform, with a loaded

2325
02:46:25,601 --> 02:46:35,120
gun and a pocket full of gunpowder, and made
his way towards the market district of Paris.

2326
02:46:35,120 --> 02:46:36,920
CHAPTER TWELVE

2327
02:46:36,920 --> 02:46:38,170
Fight to the Death

2328
02:46:38,170 --> 02:46:45,561
During the night, the thirty-seven remaining
rebels strengthened the main barricade and

2329
02:46:45,561 --> 02:46:47,700
made more bullets.

2330
02:46:47,700 --> 02:46:52,160
The ground floor of the wine shop became a
hospital for the wounded, and the bodies of

2331
02:46:52,160 --> 02:46:56,010
the dead were taken to an alley near the smaller
of the two barricades.

2332
02:46:56,010 --> 02:47:03,410
Four of the dead people were National Guards,
and their uniforms were removed.

2333
02:47:03,410 --> 02:47:08,210
After a long discussion with his friends,
Enjolras decided that the married men (there

2334
02:47:08,210 --> 02:47:11,200
were five of them) had to leave.

2335
02:47:11,200 --> 02:47:14,450
'It's your duty not to die,' he told them.

2336
02:47:14,450 --> 02:47:15,960
'You must return to your families.'

2337
02:47:15,960 --> 02:47:18,120
'How can we leave?'

2338
02:47:18,120 --> 02:47:19,149
they protested.

2339
02:47:19,149 --> 02:47:20,170
'We're surrounded.

2340
02:47:20,170 --> 02:47:23,930
The soldiers will shoot us as soon as they
see us.'

2341
02:47:23,930 --> 02:47:25,510
'You can wear these.'

2342
02:47:25,510 --> 02:47:31,430
Enjolras pointed to the National Guard uniforms
that had been taken off the dead soldiers.

2343
02:47:31,430 --> 02:47:35,810
'But there are only four,' Marius observed.

2344
02:47:35,810 --> 02:47:41,450
'Then one of us must stay and fight,' one
of the married men replied.

2345
02:47:41,450 --> 02:47:46,170
A long argument followed, during which each
of the married men tried to persuade the others

2346
02:47:46,170 --> 02:47:47,670
to go.

2347
02:47:47,670 --> 02:47:54,540
Finally, someone shouted to Marius, 'You decide
which one must stay.'

2348
02:47:54,540 --> 02:47:59,440
Marius went pale at the thought of having
to choose which man had to die.

2349
02:47:59,440 --> 02:48:08,149
He stared down at the four uniforms but, as
he did so, a fifth uniform fell as if by magic

2350
02:48:08,149 --> 02:48:10,680
at his feet.

2351
02:48:10,680 --> 02:48:15,040
Looking round, Marius recognized Cosette's
father.

2352
02:48:15,040 --> 02:48:20,910
Jean Valjean, who had arrived unnoticed at
the barricade, had been listening to the argument

2353
02:48:20,910 --> 02:48:24,540
and had quickly understood the situation.

2354
02:48:24,540 --> 02:48:29,061
'Now you can all leave,' he said.

2355
02:48:29,061 --> 02:48:34,950
The sky grew lighter, but not a door or window
was open in the street.

2356
02:48:34,950 --> 02:48:39,330
The barricade was stronger than it had been
for the first assault, and the rebels were

2357
02:48:39,330 --> 02:48:43,490
at their positions, guns loaded and ready
for action.

2358
02:48:43,490 --> 02:48:46,510
They did not have long to wait.

2359
02:48:46,510 --> 02:48:51,170
Sounds of chains and of heavy wheels moving
along the stone streets could be heard, and

2360
02:48:51,170 --> 02:48:57,040
then soldiers came into view at the end of
the street, pulling a large cannon.

2361
02:48:57,040 --> 02:49:03,250
The rebels fired their guns but, when the
smoke had cleared, they saw the soldiers,

2362
02:49:03,250 --> 02:49:08,290
unharmed, steadily aiming the cannon at the
barricade.

2363
02:49:08,290 --> 02:49:13,300
Moments later, an officer shouted a command
and the cannon roared into action.

2364
02:49:13,300 --> 02:49:18,420
The cannonball crashed into the bottom of
the barricade with a loud explosion, but did

2365
02:49:18,420 --> 02:49:20,080
little damage.

2366
02:49:20,080 --> 02:49:23,530
The rebels clapped and cheered.

2367
02:49:23,530 --> 02:49:28,489
More soldiers moved into position at the end
of the street, behind the cannon, and started

2368
02:49:28,489 --> 02:49:32,970
to build a low wall with pieces of broken
stone.

2369
02:49:32,970 --> 02:49:38,540
At the same time, the leader of the gun crew
adjusted the aim of the cannon.

2370
02:49:38,540 --> 02:49:40,610
'Heads down!'

2371
02:49:40,610 --> 02:49:42,670
Enjolras shouted.

2372
02:49:42,670 --> 02:49:48,380
The next cannonball exploded against the wall
at one end of the barricade, killing two men

2373
02:49:48,380 --> 02:49:49,840
and wounding three.

2374
02:49:49,840 --> 02:49:54,640
'We mustn't let that happen again,' Enjolras
said.

2375
02:49:54,640 --> 02:49:59,970
He aimed his gun over the barricade at the
leader of the gun crew, and fired.

2376
02:49:59,970 --> 02:50:06,140
The gunner - a fair-haired, handsome young
man - spun round twice with his head thrown

2377
02:50:06,140 --> 02:50:09,410
back, and fell sideways across the cannon.

2378
02:50:09,410 --> 02:50:12,830
Blood poured from the middle of his back.

2379
02:50:12,830 --> 02:50:16,310
A tear rolled down Enjolras's cheek.

2380
02:50:16,310 --> 02:50:21,450
'It's sad,' he murmured to Marius, who was
standing next to him.

2381
02:50:21,450 --> 02:50:25,470
'He looked a brave young man.'

2382
02:50:25,470 --> 02:50:26,470
***

2383
02:50:26,470 --> 02:50:31,210
The battle continued for some time; the cannon
destroyed the upper windows of the wine shop,

2384
02:50:31,210 --> 02:50:36,130
and did some damage to the barricade, but
the rebels did not withdraw.

2385
02:50:36,130 --> 02:50:40,439
They fired back at the soldiers, killing many
men.

2386
02:50:40,439 --> 02:50:44,779
In the pauses between shooting, the rebels
could hear the sound of fighting in other

2387
02:50:44,779 --> 02:50:46,850
parts of Paris.

2388
02:50:46,850 --> 02:50:53,450
They were filled with hope that help would
come soon, but the hope did not last long.

2389
02:50:53,450 --> 02:50:58,910
Within half an hour the sound of gunfire in
other places had stopped, and the rebels knew

2390
02:50:58,910 --> 02:51:01,029
that they were alone.

2391
02:51:01,029 --> 02:51:06,080
When a second cannon was moved into position
next to the first, they knew that the end

2392
02:51:06,080 --> 02:51:08,130
was near.

2393
02:51:08,130 --> 02:51:13,350
Both cannons fired together, accompanied by
gunfire from soldiers at the end of the street

2394
02:51:13,350 --> 02:51:15,640
and on the rooftops.

2395
02:51:15,640 --> 02:51:21,540
As other guns began firing at the smaller
barricade, the rebels fought back bravely,

2396
02:51:21,540 --> 02:51:24,220
but they were running out of bullets.

2397
02:51:24,220 --> 02:51:29,090
There were only twenty-six men left, and the
main attack on the barricade was going to

2398
02:51:29,090 --> 02:51:31,940
take place very soon.

2399
02:51:31,940 --> 02:51:37,470
Some men, including Marius, stayed on the
main barricade, while the others built a low

2400
02:51:37,470 --> 02:51:40,989
stone wall around the door of the wine shop.

2401
02:51:40,989 --> 02:51:47,641
Enjolras, inside the wine shop, turned to
Javert, who was still tied to the post.

2402
02:51:47,641 --> 02:51:52,740
'I haven't forgotten you,' he said, putting
a loaded gun on the table.

2403
02:51:52,740 --> 02:51:57,050
'The last man to leave this place will blow
your brains out.'

2404
02:51:57,050 --> 02:52:02,250
At this point, Jean Valjean spoke to Enjolras.

2405
02:52:02,250 --> 02:52:05,460
'You're the leader, aren't you?

2406
02:52:05,460 --> 02:52:08,450
Can I ask you for a favour?'

2407
02:52:08,450 --> 02:52:11,110
'You saved a man's life by giving him your
uniform.

2408
02:52:11,110 --> 02:52:13,050
You deserve some reward.

2409
02:52:13,050 --> 02:52:14,850
What do you want?'

2410
02:52:14,850 --> 02:52:17,610
'Let me kill this man.'

2411
02:52:17,610 --> 02:52:22,740
'That's fair,' Enjolras decided, when nobody
objected.

2412
02:52:22,740 --> 02:52:24,380
'You can have your spy.'

2413
02:52:24,380 --> 02:52:32,210
At the same moment there was the sound of
a drum, followed by a loud roar.

2414
02:52:32,210 --> 02:52:34,090
'They're coming!'

2415
02:52:34,090 --> 02:52:37,010
cried Marius from the top of the barricade.

2416
02:52:37,010 --> 02:52:42,540
The rebels rushed to their positions, leaving
Valjean alone with Javert inside the wine

2417
02:52:42,540 --> 02:52:44,850
shop.

2418
02:52:44,850 --> 02:52:50,540
Valjean untied the rope around Javert's feet
and, taking him by the belt of his coat, led

2419
02:52:50,540 --> 02:52:53,069
him outside.

2420
02:52:53,069 --> 02:52:58,990
Only Marius, looking over his shoulder, saw
them cross the stronghold towards the smaller

2421
02:52:58,990 --> 02:53:00,160
barricade.

2422
02:53:00,160 --> 02:53:06,680
Valjean, his gun in one hand, pulled Javert
behind him over the barricade and into a narrow

2423
02:53:06,680 --> 02:53:10,110
alley, where the corner of a house hid them
from view.

2424
02:53:10,110 --> 02:53:16,350
A terrible heap of dead bodies lay not far
away, among them the blood-stained body of

2425
02:53:16,350 --> 02:53:20,150
a young girl in man's clothes - Eponine.

2426
02:53:20,150 --> 02:53:27,069
Javert glanced at the dead body and murmured,
'I think I know that girl.

2427
02:53:27,069 --> 02:53:35,689
'Then, returning his attention to Valjean,
he said calmly, 'I think you know me, too.

2428
02:53:35,689 --> 02:53:36,689
Take your revenge.'

2429
02:53:36,689 --> 02:53:45,180
Valjean, however, took a knife from his pocket
and cut the ropes that tied Javert's wrists.

2430
02:53:45,180 --> 02:53:49,200
'You're free to go,' he said.

2431
02:53:49,200 --> 02:53:56,050
When Javert stared at him, speechless with
surprise, Valjean went on, I don't suppose

2432
02:53:56,050 --> 02:53:58,130
I'll leave here alive.

2433
02:53:58,130 --> 02:54:03,200
But if I do, I'm staying at Number 7, rue
de l'Homme-Arme.

2434
02:54:03,200 --> 02:54:05,690
Now go.'

2435
02:54:05,690 --> 02:54:10,790
Javert buttoned his coat, straightened his
shoulders and, with a puzzled look on his

2436
02:54:10,790 --> 02:54:15,510
face, began to walk off in the direction of
the market.

2437
02:54:15,510 --> 02:54:20,130
He had only gone a few steps, however, when
he turned and looked at Valjean.

2438
02:54:20,130 --> 02:54:24,340
'I find this embarrassing,' he said.

2439
02:54:24,340 --> 02:54:28,480
'I'd rather you killed me.'

2440
02:54:28,480 --> 02:54:33,609
'Go away,' Valjean replied.

2441
02:54:33,609 --> 02:54:39,830
Javert walked away slowly and Valjean, waiting
for him to turn a corner, fired his gun into

2442
02:54:39,830 --> 02:54:44,500
the air and returned to the stronghold.

2443
02:54:44,500 --> 02:54:48,949
'It's done,' he said.

2444
02:54:48,949 --> 02:54:49,949
***

2445
02:54:49,949 --> 02:54:54,490
There was a roar of gunfire and the soldiers
attacked, rushing towards the barricade.

2446
02:54:54,490 --> 02:54:57,880
Many fell, but many more reached the barricade.

2447
02:54:57,880 --> 02:55:02,970
The first assault was beaten back by the brave
rebels, but the soldiers attacked again and

2448
02:55:02,970 --> 02:55:03,970
again.

2449
02:55:03,970 --> 02:55:09,330
Soon, the ground below the barricade was piled
with dead and wounded men as the rebels and

2450
02:55:09,330 --> 02:55:12,410
soldiers fought hand to hand.

2451
02:55:12,410 --> 02:55:17,970
The rebels fought long and hard to defend
the stronghold, but finally they had to withdraw

2452
02:55:17,970 --> 02:55:21,979
to the low wall outside the wine shop.

2453
02:55:21,979 --> 02:55:26,640
They stood with their backs to the door, shooting
up at the soldiers who were climbing down

2454
02:55:26,640 --> 02:55:29,851
towards them from the barricade.

2455
02:55:29,851 --> 02:55:36,670
One by one the remaining rebels escaped into
the wine shop, until only Enjolras and Marius

2456
02:55:36,670 --> 02:55:39,060
were left outside.

2457
02:55:39,060 --> 02:55:44,560
As the two friends moved back towards the
door, fighting off the soldiers, a bullet

2458
02:55:44,560 --> 02:55:47,330
hit Marius in the shoulder.

2459
02:55:47,330 --> 02:55:53,210
His eyes closed and, in great pain, he felt
a hand grab him as he fell.

2460
02:55:53,210 --> 02:55:59,100
'They've taken me prisoner,' he thought, moments
before losing consciousness.

2461
02:55:59,100 --> 02:56:03,000
'Now I shall be shot.'

2462
02:56:03,000 --> 02:56:06,760
The soldiers, meanwhile, attacked the wine
shop.

2463
02:56:06,760 --> 02:56:09,779
Before long, they broke down the door and
rushed inside.

2464
02:56:09,779 --> 02:56:15,899
Enjolras and the few surviving rebels fought
bravely, but the soldiers were too strong.

2465
02:56:15,899 --> 02:56:22,720
Soon, all the rebels were dead, including
Enjolras, who was the last to die.

2466
02:56:22,720 --> 02:56:27,870
Sword in hand, surrounded by soldiers, he
refused to surrender.

2467
02:56:27,870 --> 02:56:35,160
He died in a rain of bullets with a strangely
victorious smile on his lips.

2468
02:56:35,160 --> 02:56:37,439
CHAPTER THIRTEEN

2469
02:56:37,439 --> 02:56:42,069
The Sewers of Paris

2470
02:56:42,069 --> 02:56:47,040
Marius had indeed been taken prisoner, but
not by the soldiers.

2471
02:56:47,040 --> 02:56:52,010
It was Jean Valjean's hand that had caught
him as he fell.

2472
02:56:52,010 --> 02:56:54,600
Valjean had taken no part in the battle.

2473
02:56:54,600 --> 02:56:59,811
He had been looking after wounded men while
bullets flew all around him.

2474
02:56:59,811 --> 02:57:05,550
When Marius had been hit, Valjean ran to him
at once, grabbed him before he fell and carried

2475
02:57:05,550 --> 02:57:10,090
his unconscious body into a small alley behind
the wine shop.

2476
02:57:10,090 --> 02:57:16,080
Valjean lowered Marius to the ground, stood
with his back to the wall and looked around

2477
02:57:16,080 --> 02:57:17,600
him.

2478
02:57:17,600 --> 02:57:19,450
The situation was terrible.

2479
02:57:19,450 --> 02:57:21,950
There seemed to be no escape.

2480
02:57:21,950 --> 02:57:24,540
On one side of him was the field of battle.

2481
02:57:24,540 --> 02:57:30,170
On the other side was the low barricade, behind
which hundreds of soldiers waited for rebels

2482
02:57:30,170 --> 02:57:31,590
trying to escape.

2483
02:57:31,590 --> 02:57:35,160
Both ways meant certain death.

2484
02:57:35,160 --> 02:57:39,290
It was a situation that only a bird could
have escaped from.

2485
02:57:39,290 --> 02:57:46,380
Valjean looked desperately around him, at
the house opposite, the barricade, the ground.

2486
02:57:46,380 --> 02:57:50,080
And then he had a sudden idea!

2487
02:57:50,080 --> 02:57:56,000
At the foot of the smaller barricade, half-hidden
by broken stones and pieces of wood, there

2488
02:57:56,000 --> 02:58:00,880
was a hole in the road covered with an iron
grille.

2489
02:58:00,880 --> 02:58:08,800
Valjean leapt forward and, using all his strength,
he moved the stones and wood, opened the grille,

2490
02:58:08,800 --> 02:58:15,220
lifted Marius on to his shoulders and climbed
down into the darkness.

2491
02:58:15,220 --> 02:58:21,939
A few minutes later, he found himself in a
long underground passage, a place of absolute

2492
02:58:21,939 --> 02:58:24,420
peace and silence.

2493
02:58:24,420 --> 02:58:27,890
He was inside the Paris sewers.

2494
02:58:27,890 --> 02:58:32,960
He could just see, by the grey light from
the grille above his head, that he was surrounded

2495
02:58:32,960 --> 02:58:34,271
by walls.

2496
02:58:34,271 --> 02:58:39,790
Ahead of him lay total darkness, but he had
to go on.

2497
02:58:39,790 --> 02:58:44,489
The soldiers might discover the grille by
the barricade at any moment, and come down

2498
02:58:44,489 --> 02:58:47,200
in search of him.

2499
02:58:47,200 --> 02:58:52,810
With Marius lying across his shoulders, Valjean
walked forward into the darkness, feeling

2500
02:58:52,810 --> 02:58:57,120
his way along the wet, slippery walls with
his hands.

2501
02:58:57,120 --> 02:59:02,850
He moved from one passage into another, slipping
several times on the wet floor.

2502
02:59:02,850 --> 02:59:08,070
He could not see where he was going, but he
knew he had to follow the downward slope of

2503
02:59:08,070 --> 02:59:11,270
the passages towards the river.

2504
02:59:11,270 --> 02:59:16,910
He walked blindly downwards in this way for
a long time, his clothes wet with the blood

2505
02:59:16,910 --> 02:59:23,510
from Marius's wound, the faint whisper of
the young man's breath in his ear.

2506
02:59:23,510 --> 02:59:29,840
He walked in total darkness, the silence broken
occasionally by the thunder of gun carriages

2507
02:59:29,840 --> 02:59:35,040
and horses racing along the streets of Paris
far above his head.

2508
02:59:35,040 --> 02:59:41,061
Suddenly, he saw his own shadow on the floor
of the passage in front of him.

2509
02:59:41,061 --> 02:59:45,529
Looking back, he saw the distant light of
a torch.

2510
02:59:45,529 --> 02:59:48,120
He was being followed!

2511
02:59:48,120 --> 02:59:52,950
He pressed himself against the wall, held
his breath and waited.

2512
02:59:52,950 --> 02:59:58,489
In the distance, a group of men formed a circle
around the torchlight.

2513
02:59:58,489 --> 03:00:03,430
They seemed to be listening for something,
waiting for someone to move.

2514
03:00:03,430 --> 03:00:09,640
Finally, the group of men moved off along
another passage, and Valjean was left in total

2515
03:00:09,640 --> 03:00:12,670
darkness once again.

2516
03:00:12,670 --> 03:00:16,540
He continued his journey through the sewers.

2517
03:00:16,540 --> 03:00:21,830
Sometimes the roof of the passages was so
low that he had to bend down as he walked.

2518
03:00:21,830 --> 03:00:27,609
His feet slipped all the time in the water
on the ground, and he felt sick and faint

2519
03:00:27,609 --> 03:00:31,120
with the terrible, airless smell.

2520
03:00:31,120 --> 03:00:37,170
At last, exhausted, he stopped beneath a large
grille that brought him much-needed light

2521
03:00:37,170 --> 03:00:39,561
and fresh air.

2522
03:00:39,561 --> 03:00:45,380
He laid Marius down gently at the edge of
the sewer, and looked down at his face.

2523
03:00:45,380 --> 03:00:50,100
It was covered with blood and as pale as death.

2524
03:00:50,100 --> 03:00:55,450
Valjean tore pieces oft his own shirt and
bandaged Marius's wounded shoulder as well

2525
03:00:55,450 --> 03:00:56,729
as he could.

2526
03:00:56,729 --> 03:01:05,450
Then, bending over the unconscious body, Valjean
stared at Marius with hatred in his eyes.

2527
03:01:05,450 --> 03:01:13,189
He found two objects in Marius's clothing:
a piece of bread and a wallet.

2528
03:01:13,189 --> 03:01:21,080
Valjean ate the bread and, opening the wallet,
found a note which Marius had written:

2529
03:01:21,080 --> 03:01:24,279
My name is Marius Pontmercy.

2530
03:01:24,279 --> 03:01:32,940
My body must be taken to the house of my grandfather,
M. Gillenormand, 6 rue des Filles-du- Calvaire,

2531
03:01:32,940 --> 03:01:36,120
in the Marais.

2532
03:01:36,120 --> 03:01:41,200
Valjean repeated the address until he could
remember it, returned the wallet to Marius's

2533
03:01:41,200 --> 03:01:49,150
pocket, picked Marius up again and continued
his journey downwards towards the river.

2534
03:01:49,150 --> 03:01:55,260
He did not know what part of the city he was
passing under or how far he had come.

2535
03:01:55,260 --> 03:02:00,300
The only thing he was sure of was that the
light through the grilles far above his head

2536
03:02:00,300 --> 03:02:05,420
was growing weaker, which meant that the sun
was setting.

2537
03:02:05,420 --> 03:02:11,170
At one point he had to walk waist-deep through
water, and almost sank as the ground turned

2538
03:02:11,170 --> 03:02:13,490
to sand beneath his feet.

2539
03:02:13,490 --> 03:02:19,450
Finally, when even his great strength was
beginning to fade, he saw ahead of him a light

2540
03:02:19,450 --> 03:02:22,840
- the clear light of day.

2541
03:02:22,840 --> 03:02:27,770
He was suddenly filled with new energy at
the sight, at last, of his way of escape from

2542
03:02:27,770 --> 03:02:29,680
the sewers.

2543
03:02:29,680 --> 03:02:35,450
Forgetting the weight of Marius on his shoulders
and his own hunger and tiredness, he ran towards

2544
03:02:35,450 --> 03:02:37,000
the light.

2545
03:02:37,000 --> 03:02:43,090
He had to bend as the roof of the tunnel became
lower, but when he reached the light, Valjean

2546
03:02:43,090 --> 03:02:46,530
stopped and gave a cry of despair.

2547
03:02:46,530 --> 03:02:54,020
The opening was closed with a strong iron
gate, held firm by a huge, rusty lock.

2548
03:02:54,020 --> 03:03:00,720
Through the bars, Valjean could see daylight,
the river, a narrow riverbank - but how could

2549
03:03:00,720 --> 03:03:03,350
he get out?

2550
03:03:03,350 --> 03:03:07,660
Valjean laid Marius down by the wall, where
the floor was dry.

2551
03:03:07,660 --> 03:03:13,029
Then, moving to the gate, he shook it fiercely
with both hands, trying to bend the bars with

2552
03:03:13,029 --> 03:03:15,250
the last of his strength.

2553
03:03:15,250 --> 03:03:19,900
But the gate was solid and the bars were firm.

2554
03:03:19,900 --> 03:03:25,040
Valjean turned his back to the gate and sank
to the ground, his head bowed between his

2555
03:03:25,040 --> 03:03:26,670
knees.

2556
03:03:26,670 --> 03:03:35,920
There was no way out and, as all hope of escape
left him, he began to think of Cosette.

2557
03:03:35,920 --> 03:03:36,920
***

2558
03:03:36,920 --> 03:03:41,660
While in this state of despair, Valjean felt
a hand on his shoulder.

2559
03:03:41,660 --> 03:03:43,800
He thought he was dreaming.

2560
03:03:43,800 --> 03:03:50,130
He looked up and saw a man dressed in old
clothes standing beside him.

2561
03:03:50,130 --> 03:03:55,930
Despite the unexpectedness of this meeting,
Valjean recognized the man at once.

2562
03:03:55,930 --> 03:03:58,899
It was Thenardier.

2563
03:03:58,899 --> 03:04:04,189
Valjean did not show that he recognized the
man, and saw with relief that Thenardier had

2564
03:04:04,189 --> 03:04:06,430
not recognized him.

2565
03:04:06,430 --> 03:04:10,440
'I'll make a bargain with you,' the man said.

2566
03:04:10,440 --> 03:04:12,350
'What do you mean?'

2567
03:04:12,350 --> 03:04:16,650
Thenardier nodded in Marius's direction.

2568
03:04:16,650 --> 03:04:18,950
'You've killed a man.

2569
03:04:18,950 --> 03:04:25,779
Give me half of what you found in this man's
pockets, and I'll unlock the gate for you.'

2570
03:04:25,779 --> 03:04:29,880
He produced a large key from his pocket, and
a piece of rope.

2571
03:04:29,880 --> 03:04:33,010
'I'll give you this as well,' he said.

2572
03:04:33,010 --> 03:04:39,760
'Then you can tie stones to the body and throw
it in the river.'

2573
03:04:39,760 --> 03:04:42,260
Valjean took the rope without speaking.

2574
03:04:42,260 --> 03:04:47,819
'What about my share of the money?'Thenardier
asked.

2575
03:04:47,819 --> 03:04:53,320
Valjean took thirty francs from his pockets
and showed it to Thenardier, who stared with

2576
03:04:53,320 --> 03:04:54,320
disbelief.

2577
03:04:54,320 --> 03:04:57,780
'You killed a man for just thirty francs?

2578
03:04:57,780 --> 03:05:00,409
You're a fool.'

2579
03:05:00,409 --> 03:05:05,080
He searched Marius's pockets himself, and
then Valjean's.

2580
03:05:05,080 --> 03:05:07,860
'It's true,' he said at last.

2581
03:05:07,860 --> 03:05:09,960
'That's all there is.

2582
03:05:09,960 --> 03:05:11,010
Oh well.

2583
03:05:11,010 --> 03:05:14,580
Never say that I'm not a kind man.'

2584
03:05:14,580 --> 03:05:20,479
He took the thirty francs and, helping Valjean
to lift Marius on to his shoulders, he put

2585
03:05:20,479 --> 03:05:27,490
the key in the lock and opened the gate just
wide enough for Valjean to pass through.

2586
03:05:27,490 --> 03:05:33,591
When Valjean was outside, Thenardier closed
the gate behind him and disappeared, like

2587
03:05:33,591 --> 03:05:38,869
a rat, into the darkness of the sewers.

2588
03:05:38,869 --> 03:05:39,869
***

2589
03:05:39,869 --> 03:05:44,570
Valjean laid Marius gently on the grass and
stood up, surrounded by silence, enjoying

2590
03:05:44,570 --> 03:05:47,600
the feeling of fresh air on his face.

2591
03:05:47,600 --> 03:05:54,050
Then, just as he was bending to splash water
from the river on Marius's face, he was aware

2592
03:05:54,050 --> 03:05:57,420
of someone else standing behind him.

2593
03:05:57,420 --> 03:06:04,120
He looked round quickly and saw a tall man
in a long coat, a large stick in his hand.

2594
03:06:04,120 --> 03:06:11,400
Although the man's face was hidden in shadow,
Valjean recognized him as Inspector Javert.

2595
03:06:11,400 --> 03:06:16,250
Javert, however, did not recognize Valjean
at first.

2596
03:06:16,250 --> 03:06:20,950
He had been more interested in catching Thenardier,
who had escaped from prison and was known

2597
03:06:20,950 --> 03:06:23,050
to be in the area.

2598
03:06:23,050 --> 03:06:27,210
'Who are you?' he asked.

2599
03:06:27,210 --> 03:06:33,080
Valjean told him his name and stood, without
moving, as Javert approached and stared into

2600
03:06:33,080 --> 03:06:34,859
his eyes.

2601
03:06:34,859 --> 03:06:39,080
'Inspector Javert,' Valjean said quietly.

2602
03:06:39,080 --> 03:06:42,260
'I beg you to do me one favour.

2603
03:06:42,260 --> 03:06:46,239
I promise not to try and escape.

2604
03:06:46,239 --> 03:06:51,330
I gave you my address this morning, if you
remember, so you would know where to find

2605
03:06:51,330 --> 03:06:53,660
me anyway.'

2606
03:06:53,660 --> 03:06:56,109
Javert did not seem to hear.

2607
03:06:56,109 --> 03:07:01,601
He stared into Valjean's eyes for a long time,
then, stepping back with a look of confusion

2608
03:07:01,601 --> 03:07:07,300
in his eyes, asked dreamily, 'What are you
doing here?

2609
03:07:07,300 --> 03:07:10,181
Who is this man?'

2610
03:07:10,181 --> 03:07:14,200
'Will you help me to take him home?'

2611
03:07:14,200 --> 03:07:15,240
Valjean said.

2612
03:07:15,240 --> 03:07:18,319
'He's badly injured.'

2613
03:07:18,319 --> 03:07:21,780
Javert looked unhappy, but he did not refuse.

2614
03:07:21,780 --> 03:07:27,340
Bending down, he took a handkerchief from
his pocket, wet it in the river and bathed

2615
03:07:27,340 --> 03:07:30,040
Marius's blood-stained forehead.

2616
03:07:30,040 --> 03:07:33,729
Then he felt Marius's wrist.

2617
03:07:33,729 --> 03:07:35,989
'He's dead,' he said.

2618
03:07:35,989 --> 03:07:42,340
'No, not yet,' Valjean replied, feeling in
Marius's jacket for the wallet.

2619
03:07:42,340 --> 03:07:47,490
'Look,' he said, showing Javert the note with
Marius's grandfather's address.

2620
03:07:47,490 --> 03:07:51,229
'That's where we need to take him.'

2621
03:07:51,229 --> 03:07:55,439
Javert shouted to the driver who was waiting
for him to bring his carriage close to the

2622
03:07:55,439 --> 03:07:56,630
river.

2623
03:07:56,630 --> 03:08:01,779
With Marius in the back seat, Valjean and
Javert side by side in the front, the carriage

2624
03:08:01,779 --> 03:08:08,931
drove off quickly through the dark and strangely
empty streets of Paris.

2625
03:08:08,931 --> 03:08:14,140
When they arrived at M. Gillenormand's house,
a servant answered the door.

2626
03:08:14,140 --> 03:08:17,351
'Does M. Gillenormand live here?'

2627
03:08:17,351 --> 03:08:18,590
Javert asked.

2628
03:08:18,590 --> 03:08:19,830
'Yes.

2629
03:08:19,830 --> 03:08:21,240
What do you want?'

2630
03:08:21,240 --> 03:08:23,931
'We're bringing back his grandson.

2631
03:08:23,931 --> 03:08:25,391
He's dead.

2632
03:08:25,391 --> 03:08:26,840
Go and wake his grandfather.

2633
03:08:26,840 --> 03:08:28,430
We're bringing him in.'

2634
03:08:28,430 --> 03:08:35,380
Javert, Valjean and the driver carried Marius
into the house and laid him gently on a sofa

2635
03:08:35,380 --> 03:08:38,689
in M. Gillenormand's sitting-room.

2636
03:08:38,689 --> 03:08:44,710
While one servant ran to find a doctor and
another looked for clean sheets, Valjean felt

2637
03:08:44,710 --> 03:08:47,630
Javert's hand on his arm.

2638
03:08:47,630 --> 03:08:53,020
He understood, and went downstairs with Javert
close behind him.

2639
03:08:53,020 --> 03:08:59,550
When they had got back into the carriage,
however, Valjean said, 'Inspector, will you

2640
03:08:59,550 --> 03:09:03,540
do one last thing for me before you arrest
me?'

2641
03:09:03,540 --> 03:09:05,700
'What is it?

2642
03:09:05,700 --> 03:09:08,710
'Javert replied impatiently.

2643
03:09:08,710 --> 03:09:11,520
'Let me go home for a minute.

2644
03:09:11,520 --> 03:09:16,340
After that, you can do whatever you want with
me.'

2645
03:09:16,340 --> 03:09:21,890
Javert was silent for some moments, his chin
sunk in the collar of his overcoat.

2646
03:09:21,890 --> 03:09:24,439
Then he pulled down the window in front of
him.

2647
03:09:24,439 --> 03:09:31,149
'Number 7, rue de l'Homme-Arme,' he told the
driver.

2648
03:09:31,149 --> 03:09:33,650
Neither man spoke during the journey.

2649
03:09:33,650 --> 03:09:38,770
At the end of the rue de l'Homme-Arme, which
was too narrow for the carriage to enter,

2650
03:09:38,770 --> 03:09:44,489
Javert paid the driver and accompanied Valjean
to his front door on foot.

2651
03:09:44,489 --> 03:09:50,620
'Go in,' said Javert, with a strange, distant
look in his eyes.

2652
03:09:50,620 --> 03:09:52,840
'I'll wait for you here.'

2653
03:09:52,840 --> 03:09:57,729
Valjean went into his house and called, 'It's
me!'

2654
03:09:57,729 --> 03:10:03,330
Climbing the stairs, he paused for a moment
to look out of the window to see what Javert

2655
03:10:03,330 --> 03:10:05,540
was doing.

2656
03:10:05,540 --> 03:10:10,870
But the street was empty; there was no one
there.

2657
03:10:10,870 --> 03:10:17,910
The next morning, Inspector Javert's body
was discovered floating in the river.

2658
03:10:17,910 --> 03:10:23,689
The poor man, unable to understand the kindness
and gentle nature of the man he had spent

2659
03:10:23,689 --> 03:10:30,900
his whole life hating, had taken his own life
by jumping from a bridge.

2660
03:10:30,900 --> 03:10:39,840
It was the only way he knew to escape the
confusion that was poisoning his heart.

2661
03:10:39,840 --> 03:10:40,840
***

2662
03:10:40,840 --> 03:10:46,910
When M. Gillenormand saw his pale, lifeless-looking
grandson lying on the sofa, he shook from

2663
03:10:46,910 --> 03:10:48,410
head to foot.

2664
03:10:48,410 --> 03:10:53,290
Leaning against the door for support, he murmured,
'Marius!'

2665
03:10:53,290 --> 03:10:56,910
'He has just been brought here,' said a servant.

2666
03:10:56,910 --> 03:10:58,840
'He was on the barricade and

2667
03:10:58,840 --> 03:11:01,649
'He's dead!'

2668
03:11:01,649 --> 03:11:03,979
cried the old man in a terrible voice.

2669
03:11:03,979 --> 03:11:05,680
'The fool!

2670
03:11:05,680 --> 03:11:09,109
He did this to hurt me, the ungrateful boy.

2671
03:11:09,109 --> 03:11:16,210
I try to be good to him, and this is how he
rewards me!'

2672
03:11:16,210 --> 03:11:20,600
The old man walked to the window and, while
he complained to the night about the pain

2673
03:11:20,600 --> 03:11:26,020
and grief his grandson had caused him, the
doctor arrived.

2674
03:11:26,020 --> 03:11:32,080
After listening to Marius's heart, he organized
his removal to a bed in another room, and

2675
03:11:32,080 --> 03:11:36,300
returned to M. Gillenormand, who was still
standing by the window.

2676
03:11:36,300 --> 03:11:38,729
'Will he live?'

2677
03:11:38,729 --> 03:11:43,440
M. Gillenormand asked, his eyes wild with
fear.

2678
03:11:43,440 --> 03:11:47,630
'I don't know,' the doctor replied.

2679
03:11:47,630 --> 03:11:53,960
'The wound to his body is not serious, but
there are deep cuts on his head.

2680
03:11:53,960 --> 03:12:00,480
It's difficult to say M. Gillenormand went
to Marius's bedside.

2681
03:12:00,480 --> 03:12:04,070
'You heartless boy,' he said angrily.

2682
03:12:04,070 --> 03:12:09,979
'A fool who prefers fighting to dancing and
having fun.

2683
03:12:09,979 --> 03:12:11,750
What kind of man are you?

2684
03:12:11,750 --> 03:12:14,580
Are you mad?

2685
03:12:14,580 --> 03:12:16,540
But it makes no difference.

2686
03:12:16,540 --> 03:12:19,340
I too shall die.

2687
03:12:19,340 --> 03:12:24,350
That makes you a murderer, a cold-hearted
killer.

2688
03:12:24,350 --> 03:12:27,020
I cannot feel grief for you.

2689
03:12:27,020 --> 03:12:36,899
At that moment, Marius's eyes slowly opened
and his gaze rested upon M. Gillenormand.

2690
03:12:36,899 --> 03:12:38,239
'Marius!'

2691
03:12:38,239 --> 03:12:39,920
the old man cried.

2692
03:12:39,920 --> 03:12:43,710
'Marius, my child, grandson!

2693
03:12:43,710 --> 03:12:47,500
You're alive after all!'

2694
03:12:47,500 --> 03:12:49,590
CHAPTER FOURTEEN

2695
03:12:49,590 --> 03:12:52,739
The Wedding

2696
03:12:52,739 --> 03:12:58,340
Marius lay for a long time between life and
death in a state of fever, endlessly repeating

2697
03:12:58,340 --> 03:13:00,590
the name of Cosette.

2698
03:13:00,590 --> 03:13:04,900
'He mustn't get excited,' the doctor warned.

2699
03:13:04,900 --> 03:13:09,800
Every day, according to one of the servants,
a white-haired, well-dressed gentleman came

2700
03:13:09,800 --> 03:13:12,970
to ask for news of the sick man.

2701
03:13:12,970 --> 03:13:18,950
Finally, after three months, the doctor announced
that Marius was out of danger.

2702
03:13:18,950 --> 03:13:24,939
But he had to spend the next two months resting
because of the damage to his shoulder.

2703
03:13:24,939 --> 03:13:30,450
M. Gillenormand grew happier as his grandson's
condition improved.

2704
03:13:30,450 --> 03:13:37,100
He did strange, unexpected things, like running
up and down stairs without knowing why.

2705
03:13:37,100 --> 03:13:43,080
He gave his neighbour, a pretty woman, a bunch
of flowers, which greatly annoyed her husband.

2706
03:13:43,080 --> 03:13:48,680
Marius, meanwhile, tried to make sense of
what had happened to him.

2707
03:13:48,680 --> 03:13:54,439
He thought about Enjolras and Eponine, and
wondered why Cosette's father had been at

2708
03:13:54,439 --> 03:13:56,380
the barricade.

2709
03:13:56,380 --> 03:14:01,100
He could not understand why nobody could tell
him how he had been saved.

2710
03:14:01,100 --> 03:14:06,320
All he knew was that he had been brought to
his grandfather's house in a carriage.

2711
03:14:06,320 --> 03:14:11,279
He noticed his grandfather's tenderness towards
him, but he could not forget the old man's

2712
03:14:11,279 --> 03:14:17,600
unfairness and cruelty to his father, who
had died penniless and unloved.

2713
03:14:17,600 --> 03:14:23,870
Most of all, however, he thought about Cosette,
and how he could find her again.

2714
03:14:23,870 --> 03:14:29,510
'There's something I have to say to you,'
Marius told his grandfather one day.

2715
03:14:29,510 --> 03:14:31,490
'What is it?'

2716
03:14:31,490 --> 03:14:33,340
'I want to get married.'

2717
03:14:33,340 --> 03:14:36,770
'But of course,' the old man laughed.

2718
03:14:36,770 --> 03:14:39,170
'What do you mean - of course?'

2719
03:14:39,170 --> 03:14:40,779
'That's understood.

2720
03:14:40,779 --> 03:14:43,880
You will have your little girl.'

2721
03:14:43,880 --> 03:14:49,770
'I don't understand,' Marius said, almost
speechless with amazement.

2722
03:14:49,770 --> 03:14:53,810
'You will have her,' the old man repeated.

2723
03:14:53,810 --> 03:15:00,940
'She comes here every day in the shape of
an old man who asks for news of you.

2724
03:15:00,940 --> 03:15:07,010
While you've been ill, she's spent her time
crying and making bandages for you.

2725
03:15:07,010 --> 03:15:09,840
I know all about her.

2726
03:15:09,840 --> 03:15:14,420
She lives at Number 7, rue de l'Homme-Arme.

2727
03:15:14,420 --> 03:15:17,570
You see, I'm not as unkind as you think.

2728
03:15:17,570 --> 03:15:23,350
I've found out that she's a charming girl
and that she loves you.

2729
03:15:23,350 --> 03:15:31,090
I knew you were angry with me, and I thought,
"What can I do to make him love me?"

2730
03:15:31,090 --> 03:15:35,529
Then I thought, "I can give him Cosette."

2731
03:15:35,529 --> 03:15:40,890
I wanted to invite her to see you, but the
doctor warned me that you would probably get

2732
03:15:40,890 --> 03:15:43,110
too excited.

2733
03:15:43,110 --> 03:15:49,210
So I advise you, dear boy, to eat more meat
and get better soon.

2734
03:15:49,210 --> 03:15:52,949
Then you can marry your Cosette and be happy.'

2735
03:15:52,949 --> 03:15:57,410
Having said this, the old man burst into tears.

2736
03:15:57,410 --> 03:16:02,840
He held Marius's head to his chest and they
cried together.

2737
03:16:02,840 --> 03:16:09,739
'Grandfather,' Marius said at last, 'I'm feeling
much better already.

2738
03:16:09,739 --> 03:16:10,890
When can I see her?'

2739
03:16:10,890 --> 03:16:13,550
'You can see her tomorrow.'

2740
03:16:13,550 --> 03:16:15,640
'Why not today?'

2741
03:16:15,640 --> 03:16:19,090
'All right, I'll fetch her today.

2742
03:16:19,090 --> 03:16:25,510
You've called me "grandfather"; you've shown
me that you love me after all.

2743
03:16:25,510 --> 03:16:29,909
You've earned your reward!'

2744
03:16:29,909 --> 03:16:30,909
***

2745
03:16:30,909 --> 03:16:34,520
Later that day, Cosette arrived at M. Gillenormand's
house.

2746
03:16:34,520 --> 03:16:39,830
Standing beside her on the doorstep was a
white-haired man with a strangely nervous

2747
03:16:39,830 --> 03:16:40,860
smile.

2748
03:16:40,860 --> 03:16:46,470
M. Gillenormand showed them up to the room
where Marius was waiting.

2749
03:16:46,470 --> 03:16:49,330
Cosette stood in the doorway, overcome with
happiness.

2750
03:16:49,330 --> 03:16:55,470
She wanted to throw herself into Marius's
arms, but was unable to move, afraid to show

2751
03:16:55,470 --> 03:16:57,890
the world that she loved him.

2752
03:16:57,890 --> 03:16:58,920
'Monsieur.'

2753
03:16:58,920 --> 03:17:03,160
M. Gillenormand addressed Jean Valjean.

2754
03:17:03,160 --> 03:17:11,199
'I have the honour, on behalf of my grandson,
Marius Pontmercy, to ask for your daughter's

2755
03:17:11,199 --> 03:17:14,040
hand in marriage.'

2756
03:17:14,040 --> 03:17:15,850
Jean Valjean bowed.

2757
03:17:15,850 --> 03:17:23,729
'Good, then that is agreed,' M. Gillenormand
said and, turning to Marius and Cosette, he

2758
03:17:23,729 --> 03:17:30,520
added, 'My children, you are free to love
one another.'

2759
03:17:30,520 --> 03:17:34,250
When they were alone together, Cosette and
Marius kissed.

2760
03:17:34,250 --> 03:17:37,690
'Is it really you?'

2761
03:17:37,690 --> 03:17:39,189
Cosette murmured at last.

2762
03:17:39,189 --> 03:17:41,189
'I can't believe it.

2763
03:17:41,189 --> 03:17:43,069
I'm so happy to see you.

2764
03:17:43,069 --> 03:17:47,330
I was so excited today that I haven't even
dressed up for you.

2765
03:17:47,330 --> 03:17:48,630
I must look terrible.

2766
03:17:48,630 --> 03:17:51,630
But why don't you say something?

2767
03:17:51,630 --> 03:17:54,859
Why are you letting me do all the talking?

2768
03:17:54,859 --> 03:17:57,380
Do you still love me?

2769
03:17:57,380 --> 03:17:59,529
Oh, I'm so wild with happiness

2770
03:17:59,529 --> 03:18:03,229
'My love...'

2771
03:18:03,229 --> 03:18:06,909
Marius whispered.

2772
03:18:06,909 --> 03:18:07,909
***

2773
03:18:07,909 --> 03:18:10,540
The wedding was arranged for February the
following year.

2774
03:18:10,540 --> 03:18:13,489
Jean Valjean arranged everything.

2775
03:18:13,489 --> 03:18:18,410
Having been a mayor, he knew how to solve
an awkward problem: the question of Cosette's

2776
03:18:18,410 --> 03:18:24,920
real family He told everybody that he was
not her father, but her guardian.

2777
03:18:24,920 --> 03:18:32,120
He also invented a dead family for Cosette,
so that everybody believed she was an orphan.

2778
03:18:32,120 --> 03:18:39,479
Valjean, as her guardian, gave Cosette a large
amount of money - half a million francs - but

2779
03:18:39,479 --> 03:18:42,850
did not tell her that the money was his.

2780
03:18:42,850 --> 03:18:48,590
He told her that the money came from a man
who preferred to remain unknown.

2781
03:18:48,590 --> 03:18:53,160
It was arranged that the couple, who could
not believe their sudden, new-found happiness,

2782
03:18:53,160 --> 03:18:57,350
would live with M. Gillenormand after the
wedding.

2783
03:18:57,350 --> 03:19:03,710
Cosette, accompanied by Jean Valjean, visited
Marius every day.

2784
03:19:03,710 --> 03:19:06,610
Marius did not speak much to Valjean.

2785
03:19:06,610 --> 03:19:11,330
Despite enjoying an occasional conversation
with him, he found something strange about

2786
03:19:11,330 --> 03:19:12,830
the old man.

2787
03:19:12,830 --> 03:19:17,560
He could not believe that this was the same
man he had seen at the barricade all those

2788
03:19:17,560 --> 03:19:21,670
months ago - it seemed like a bad dream to
him.

2789
03:19:21,670 --> 03:19:26,790
But there were more important things for Marius
to think about.

2790
03:19:26,790 --> 03:19:31,950
Apart from preparing for his wedding, there
were two people that he wanted to find.

2791
03:19:31,950 --> 03:19:35,250
First, there was Thenardier.

2792
03:19:35,250 --> 03:19:41,180
He was, without doubt, a bad man, but Marius
had promised his father to find him and help

2793
03:19:41,180 --> 03:19:42,380
him.

2794
03:19:42,380 --> 03:19:47,330
He employed agents to find Thenardier, but
without success.

2795
03:19:47,330 --> 03:19:53,010
The only thing they discovered was that Mme
Thenardier had died, and that her husband

2796
03:19:53,010 --> 03:19:59,649
had escaped from prison and disappeared with
his surviving daughter, Azelma.

2797
03:19:59,649 --> 03:20:04,479
Second, there was the mysterious stranger
who had saved his life.

2798
03:20:04,479 --> 03:20:10,859
Marius's attempts to find him also ended in
failure, and the true story of his escape

2799
03:20:10,859 --> 03:20:16,359
from the barricade remained a complete mystery
to him.

2800
03:20:16,359 --> 03:20:21,830
One evening, when Marius was talking to Cosette
and Jean Valjean about the mystery and his

2801
03:20:21,830 --> 03:20:27,729
unsuccessful attempts to solve it, he became
angry with Cosette's guardian's lack of interest

2802
03:20:27,729 --> 03:20:29,160
in his story.

2803
03:20:29,160 --> 03:20:32,739
'The man was a hero,' Marius said.

2804
03:20:32,739 --> 03:20:37,529
'Do you realize, Monsieur, how brave this
man was?

2805
03:20:37,529 --> 03:20:42,580
He rescued me from the field of battle and
carried me through the sewers of Paris.

2806
03:20:42,580 --> 03:20:47,030
He risked his life to save a dying man, and
why?

2807
03:20:47,030 --> 03:20:49,370
He was a total stranger.

2808
03:20:49,370 --> 03:20:51,670
He did it without any thought of a reward.

2809
03:20:51,670 --> 03:20:55,270
Oh, I wish Cosette's money were mine.'

2810
03:20:55,270 --> 03:20:58,960
'It is yours,' Valjean reminded him.

2811
03:20:58,960 --> 03:21:03,700
'I would give it all,' said Marius,'to find
that man!'

2812
03:21:03,700 --> 03:21:08,170
Jean Valjean was silent.

2813
03:21:08,170 --> 03:21:09,170
***

2814
03:21:09,170 --> 03:21:11,390
Cosette and Marius made a handsome couple
on their wedding day.

2815
03:21:11,390 --> 03:21:16,770
All previous unhappiness was forgotten as
they kissed in the church, watched proudly

2816
03:21:16,770 --> 03:21:19,970
by M. Gillenormand and Jean Valjean.

2817
03:21:19,970 --> 03:21:25,069
There were flowers everywhere when they returned
to M. Gillenormand's house for the wedding

2818
03:21:25,069 --> 03:21:26,439
feast.

2819
03:21:26,439 --> 03:21:32,450
It was the happiest night of Cosette's life,
spoilt only by one thing: the fact that her

2820
03:21:32,450 --> 03:21:38,720
guardian - whom she still thought of as her
father - went home before the feast had started,

2821
03:21:38,720 --> 03:21:41,790
saying that he felt ill.

2822
03:21:41,790 --> 03:21:44,319
But Cosette was not unhappy for long.

2823
03:21:44,319 --> 03:21:49,060
She had Marius, and she would be happy with
him for the rest of her life!

2824
03:21:49,060 --> 03:21:57,199
Jean Valjean, meanwhile, went home, lit his
candle and went upstairs to bed.

2825
03:21:57,199 --> 03:22:00,250
That night, however, he was unable to sleep.

2826
03:22:00,250 --> 03:22:05,320
He remembered the little girl he had rescued
from the Thenardiers ten years earlier, and

2827
03:22:05,320 --> 03:22:10,449
felt sad that he was no longer the most important
man in her life.

2828
03:22:10,449 --> 03:22:13,830
Another man was the centre of her universe.

2829
03:22:13,830 --> 03:22:18,910
He was proud of having helped to bring her
happiness with Marius, but another thing troubled

2830
03:22:18,910 --> 03:22:26,330
his soul: the fact that nobody, not even Cosette,
knew the truth about him.

2831
03:22:26,330 --> 03:22:32,470
That he was Jean Valjean, a criminal who had
spent nineteen years in prison and who had

2832
03:22:32,470 --> 03:22:37,710
stolen silver candlesticks from a trusting
and kind-hearted bishop.

2833
03:22:37,710 --> 03:22:44,050
He knew that if he told Cosette and Marius
the truth, he would spoil everybody's happiness

2834
03:22:44,050 --> 03:22:47,490
and he would lose their love and respect.

2835
03:22:47,490 --> 03:22:54,080
On the other hand, if he continued to lie
about his past, he would lose his own soul.

2836
03:22:54,080 --> 03:22:57,060
What could he do?

2837
03:22:57,060 --> 03:22:58,060
***

2838
03:22:58,060 --> 03:23:04,540
The next day Valjean visited M. Gillenormand's
house, and asked to speak to Marius in private.

2839
03:23:04,540 --> 03:23:10,529
Marius hugged Valjean warmly, addressed him
as 'father' and invited him to lunch, but

2840
03:23:10,529 --> 03:23:19,450
Valjean shook his head and said, 'Monsieur,
I have something to tell you.'

2841
03:23:19,450 --> 03:23:24,109
Marius listened quietly as Valjean told him
everything about his life.

2842
03:23:24,109 --> 03:23:30,620
Finally, in a state of shock and confusion,
the young man said, 'Why have you told me

2843
03:23:30,620 --> 03:23:32,030
all this?

2844
03:23:32,030 --> 03:23:34,000
No one forced you to.'

2845
03:23:34,000 --> 03:23:42,210
'If I had continued to keep my secret to myself,
I would have destroyed my own heart,' Valjean

2846
03:23:42,210 --> 03:23:43,330
replied.

2847
03:23:43,330 --> 03:23:47,160
'Besides, I belong to no family.

2848
03:23:47,160 --> 03:23:52,199
Cosette was the only family I ever had.

2849
03:23:52,199 --> 03:23:56,100
Everything ended for me when she married you
yesterday.

2850
03:23:56,100 --> 03:23:59,070
She is happy with the man she loves.

2851
03:23:59,070 --> 03:24:05,910
I tried to persuade myself that it would be
better not to admit the truth about my past,

2852
03:24:05,910 --> 03:24:07,710
but it was no use.

2853
03:24:07,710 --> 03:24:13,710
I could not silence the voice that speaks
to me when I am alone.'

2854
03:24:13,710 --> 03:24:16,370
Neither of them spoke for several minutes.

2855
03:24:16,370 --> 03:24:20,779
Then Marius murmured, 'Poor Cosette.

2856
03:24:20,779 --> 03:24:21,779
When she hears

2857
03:24:21,779 --> 03:24:24,609
'But you must promise not to tell her!'

2858
03:24:24,609 --> 03:24:26,609
Valjean interrupted.

2859
03:24:26,609 --> 03:24:30,000
'She'll be heart-broken if she hears the truth
about me.

2860
03:24:30,000 --> 03:24:32,989
I don't think I could bear it...

2861
03:24:32,989 --> 03:24:33,989
'

2862
03:24:33,989 --> 03:24:37,399
He sank into an armchair and buried his face
in his hands.

2863
03:24:37,399 --> 03:24:41,750
'Don't worry,' Marius said at last.

2864
03:24:41,750 --> 03:24:43,890
'I'll keep your secret.

2865
03:24:43,890 --> 03:24:47,720
But I think it would be better if you stopped
seeing her.'

2866
03:24:47,720 --> 03:24:53,860
'I understand,' Valjean said, rising to leave.

2867
03:24:53,860 --> 03:25:01,500
But at the door he half-turned and said, 'Monsieur,
if you will permit me, I would like to come

2868
03:25:01,500 --> 03:25:02,680
and see her.

2869
03:25:02,680 --> 03:25:06,870
I wouldn't come often or stay very long.

2870
03:25:06,870 --> 03:25:10,819
We could meet in that little room on the ground
floor.

2871
03:25:10,819 --> 03:25:18,410
Please Monsieur, if I can't see Cosette again,
I'll have nothing left to live for.

2872
03:25:18,410 --> 03:25:26,569
Besides, if I suddenly stopped visiting, people
would become suspicious and begin to talk

2873
03:25:26,569 --> 03:25:31,010
'You can come every evening,' said Marius.

2874
03:25:31,010 --> 03:25:39,810
'Monsieur, you are very kind,' said Jean Valjean,
shaking Marius's hand and leaving the room.

2875
03:25:39,810 --> 03:25:42,140
CHAPTER FIFTEEN

2876
03:25:42,140 --> 03:25:46,229
The Truth at Last

2877
03:25:46,229 --> 03:25:51,630
Marius kept his promise about not telling
Cosette, and Valjean visited her every evening

2878
03:25:51,630 --> 03:25:54,649
in a small room on the ground floor.

2879
03:25:54,649 --> 03:26:00,020
It was cold and damp, but a fire had been
lit and two armchairs had been placed in front

2880
03:26:00,020 --> 03:26:01,040
of it.

2881
03:26:01,040 --> 03:26:07,640
At first, Cosette could not understand why
Valjean refused to meet her upstairs.

2882
03:26:07,640 --> 03:26:13,239
When he refused to kiss her cheek, she began
to feel unhappy, afraid that she had done

2883
03:26:13,239 --> 03:26:15,449
something to offend him.

2884
03:26:15,449 --> 03:26:19,360
She pressed his hands in hers and held them
to her lips.

2885
03:26:19,360 --> 03:26:22,649
'Please, please be kind!'

2886
03:26:22,649 --> 03:26:23,710
she begged.

2887
03:26:23,710 --> 03:26:26,979
'I want you to come and live with us.

2888
03:26:26,979 --> 03:26:32,170
You'll always be my father and I'm not going
to let you go.'

2889
03:26:32,170 --> 03:26:34,090
He released his hands.

2890
03:26:34,090 --> 03:26:39,880
'You mustn't call me "father" any more,' he
told her.

2891
03:26:39,880 --> 03:26:42,660
'You must call me "Monsieur Jean".'

2892
03:26:42,660 --> 03:26:47,710
'I don't understand,' she said, becoming angry.

2893
03:26:47,710 --> 03:26:48,990
'This is ridiculous.

2894
03:26:48,990 --> 03:26:54,000
You're upsetting me very much, and I don't
know why you're being so cruel.'

2895
03:26:54,000 --> 03:26:56,930
'You don't need a father any more.

2896
03:26:56,930 --> 03:26:59,420
You have a husband.'

2897
03:26:59,420 --> 03:27:01,521
'What a thing to say!'

2898
03:27:01,521 --> 03:27:02,521
Cosette replied.

2899
03:27:02,521 --> 03:27:05,810
'Are you angry with me because I'm happy?'

2900
03:27:05,810 --> 03:27:11,910
'Cosette,' he said, 'your happiness is the
only thing that matters to me.

2901
03:27:11,910 --> 03:27:17,660
You're happy now, and so my work is complete.'

2902
03:27:17,660 --> 03:27:23,080
With these words, he picked up his hat and
left.

2903
03:27:23,080 --> 03:27:28,399
Jean Valjean continued his evening visits,
but the relationship between himself and Cosette

2904
03:27:28,399 --> 03:27:31,330
became cooler and more distant.

2905
03:27:31,330 --> 03:27:35,670
She stopped calling him 'father' or asking
him questions.

2906
03:27:35,670 --> 03:27:40,859
As 'Monsieur Jean', he gradually became a
different person to her, and she began not

2907
03:27:40,859 --> 03:27:43,800
to depend on him for her happiness.

2908
03:27:43,800 --> 03:27:52,000
Valjean would sit looking at Cosette in silence,
or would talk about incidents from their past.

2909
03:27:52,000 --> 03:27:57,360
One evening in April, he called at the usual
time but was told that Cosette had gone out

2910
03:27:57,360 --> 03:27:59,730
with her husband.

2911
03:27:59,730 --> 03:28:05,580
He waited in the small, damp room for an hour
before sadly returning home.

2912
03:28:05,580 --> 03:28:10,620
Over the next few days, his visits began to
be interrupted by servants calling Cosette

2913
03:28:10,620 --> 03:28:12,550
to dinner.

2914
03:28:12,550 --> 03:28:17,990
When he arrived, he discovered that the fire
had not been lit, and the armchairs had been

2915
03:28:17,990 --> 03:28:20,310
left near the door.

2916
03:28:20,310 --> 03:28:26,330
One evening he discovered there were no chairs
in the room at all - he and Cosette had to

2917
03:28:26,330 --> 03:28:30,000
stand in the cold for their whole meeting.

2918
03:28:30,000 --> 03:28:35,529
Valjean realized what was happening; Marius
was telling the servants not to make him welcome

2919
03:28:35,529 --> 03:28:37,810
any more.

2920
03:28:37,810 --> 03:28:44,940
That night he went home in despair, and the
next evening he did not come at all.

2921
03:28:44,940 --> 03:28:50,100
When Valjean did not appear for the second
evening, Cosette sent a servant to his house

2922
03:28:50,100 --> 03:28:52,859
to ask if he was well.

2923
03:28:52,859 --> 03:28:58,840
Valjean replied that he was very well, but
that he had business to attend to.

2924
03:28:58,840 --> 03:29:04,080
He did not return to the house again, and
Cosette was too busy with married life to

2925
03:29:04,080 --> 03:29:06,590
think too much about him.

2926
03:29:06,590 --> 03:29:12,960
She did not realize that, every evening, Valjean
would walk slowly from his house until he

2927
03:29:12,960 --> 03:29:16,820
reached the corner of the street where she
lived.

2928
03:29:16,820 --> 03:29:23,121
He would then stare at the house for several
minutes, tears rolling down his cheeks, before

2929
03:29:23,121 --> 03:29:28,989
turning round and slowly returning home.

2930
03:29:28,989 --> 03:29:29,989
***

2931
03:29:29,989 --> 03:29:33,710
Marius thought it was right to exclude Valjean
from Cosette's life.

2932
03:29:33,710 --> 03:29:37,750
He achieved this without cruelty, but without
weakness.

2933
03:29:37,750 --> 03:29:44,290
Apart from the details about his life that
Valjean had confessed to him, he knew that

2934
03:29:44,290 --> 03:29:48,430
Valjean had killed Inspector Javert at the
barricade.

2935
03:29:48,430 --> 03:29:55,070
His private investigations into the old man's
past had also revealed an even more disgusting

2936
03:29:55,070 --> 03:29:56,380
fact.

2937
03:29:56,380 --> 03:30:03,680
He had discovered that Valjean's money really
belonged to somebody called Monsieur Madeleine,

2938
03:30:03,680 --> 03:30:09,890
a wealthy manufacturer from Montreuil who
had mysteriously disappeared.

2939
03:30:09,890 --> 03:30:16,290
He persuaded Cosette, therefore, not to use
any of the money her guardian had given her,

2940
03:30:16,290 --> 03:30:21,649
and to live on the money that he had started
to earn as a lawyer.

2941
03:30:21,649 --> 03:30:24,170
Cosette had not been happy about this.

2942
03:30:24,170 --> 03:30:29,010
She could not understand why her father, as
she still thought of Valjean, had stopped

2943
03:30:29,010 --> 03:30:30,830
visiting her.

2944
03:30:30,830 --> 03:30:33,530
She still loved him in her heart.

2945
03:30:33,530 --> 03:30:39,040
But she loved her husband even more, and she
gradually became used to not depending on

2946
03:30:39,040 --> 03:30:43,080
the old man for her happiness.

2947
03:30:43,080 --> 03:30:51,650
One evening a servant brought Marius a letter,
saying, 'The writer is waiting in the hall.'

2948
03:30:51,650 --> 03:30:57,950
The smell of tobacco and the handwriting on
the envelope was so familiar that Marius immediately

2949
03:30:57,950 --> 03:31:00,439
thought of the Jondrettes.

2950
03:31:00,439 --> 03:31:02,330
He read the letter quickly.

2951
03:31:02,330 --> 03:31:07,870
It was signed 'Thenard', and was asking for
money.

2952
03:31:07,870 --> 03:31:10,090
Marius could not believe his luck.

2953
03:31:10,090 --> 03:31:14,890
He had tried without success to find the man
who had saved his father's lite at Waterloo,

2954
03:31:14,890 --> 03:31:18,540
and now the man had come to him!

2955
03:31:18,540 --> 03:31:22,390
He immediately asked the servant to show the
man in.

2956
03:31:22,390 --> 03:31:29,609
However, Marius had a shock when he saw the
man - he did not recognize him at all!

2957
03:31:29,609 --> 03:31:35,420
He was an old man with a big nose, glasses
and neat grey hair.

2958
03:31:35,420 --> 03:31:41,779
He was wearing smart black clothes, and a
gold watch chain hung from his jacket pocket.

2959
03:31:41,779 --> 03:31:44,680
'What do you want?'

2960
03:31:44,680 --> 03:31:48,790
Marius asked coldly, as the stranger bowed
to him.

2961
03:31:48,790 --> 03:31:53,330
The stranger explained in great detail how
he used to work for the government in foreign

2962
03:31:53,330 --> 03:31:58,870
countries and that, now he was retired, he
wanted to move to South America with his wife

2963
03:31:58,870 --> 03:32:00,490
and daughter.

2964
03:32:00,490 --> 03:32:04,390
Unfortunately, it was a long journey, and
he needed money.

2965
03:32:04,390 --> 03:32:07,340
'What has that to do with me?'

2966
03:32:07,340 --> 03:32:12,840
'Has M. Pontmercy not read my letter?'

2967
03:32:12,840 --> 03:32:17,840
Marius had only read the letter quickly, and
could not remember the details, so he said,

2968
03:32:17,840 --> 03:32:19,430
'Go on.'

2969
03:32:19,430 --> 03:32:25,580
'I have a secret to tell you, M. Pontmercy,'
the stranger said.

2970
03:32:25,580 --> 03:32:28,870
'I'll tell you the first part for nothing.

2971
03:32:28,870 --> 03:32:30,891
I think you'll be interested;

2972
03:32:30,891 --> 03:32:32,120
'Well?'

2973
03:32:32,120 --> 03:32:38,899
'The man you think is your wife's guardian
is a murderer and a thief.

2974
03:32:38,899 --> 03:32:42,010
His name is Jean Valjean.'

2975
03:32:42,010 --> 03:32:43,990
'I know that.'

2976
03:32:43,990 --> 03:32:48,270
'Did you know that he spent nineteen years
in prison?'

2977
03:32:48,270 --> 03:32:51,470
'I know that too.'

2978
03:32:51,470 --> 03:32:57,350
The stranger narrowed his eyes, trying to
hide his disappointment and anger at Marius's

2979
03:32:57,350 --> 03:32:58,350
calmness.

2980
03:32:58,350 --> 03:33:00,410
Then he gave a strange smile.

2981
03:33:00,410 --> 03:33:04,590
'I have more information to tell you.

2982
03:33:04,590 --> 03:33:09,080
It concerns money that belongs to your wife.

2983
03:33:09,080 --> 03:33:16,620
It's a remarkable secret and I'll sell the
information to you for 20,000 francs.'

2984
03:33:16,620 --> 03:33:23,260
'I know this secret already,' Marius said,
'just as I knew the others.'

2985
03:33:23,260 --> 03:33:25,240
'10,000 francs?'

2986
03:33:25,240 --> 03:33:28,800
'I repeat, you have nothing to tell me.'

2987
03:33:28,800 --> 03:33:32,130
'But I need to eat, Monsieur!'

2988
03:33:32,130 --> 03:33:34,370
the visitor said, losing confidence.

2989
03:33:34,370 --> 03:33:37,990
'I'll tell you for twenty francs.'

2990
03:33:37,990 --> 03:33:41,521
'I know it already,' Marius said.

2991
03:33:41,521 --> 03:33:42,600
'I know everything.

2992
03:33:42,600 --> 03:33:46,080
I even know your real name.

2993
03:33:46,080 --> 03:33:49,180
It's Thenardier.'

2994
03:33:49,180 --> 03:33:55,311
The visitor laughed, but Marius went on, 'You're
also Jondrette.

2995
03:33:55,311 --> 03:33:58,580
And you once had an inn in Montfermeil.'

2996
03:33:58,580 --> 03:34:01,060
'I deny it!'

2997
03:34:01,060 --> 03:34:07,290
'You're a completely rotten man, but I'll
give you this.'

2998
03:34:07,290 --> 03:34:11,590
Marius took a banknote out of his pocket and
threw it in the stranger's face.

2999
03:34:11,590 --> 03:34:14,840
'Thank you, M. Pontmercy!'

3000
03:34:14,840 --> 03:34:18,130
the man said, examining the note.

3001
03:34:18,130 --> 03:34:19,950
'500 francs!

3002
03:34:19,950 --> 03:34:21,630
That's real money.

3003
03:34:21,630 --> 03:34:28,340
Oh well, I suppose we can relax.'

3004
03:34:28,340 --> 03:34:34,771
With those words, he removed his false nose,
glasses and neat grey wig.

3005
03:34:34,771 --> 03:34:41,729
'M. Pontmercy is absolutely right,' he said,
changing his voice.

3006
03:34:41,729 --> 03:34:44,790
'I am Thenardier.'

3007
03:34:44,790 --> 03:34:48,790
He waited for a few seconds to see Marius's
reaction.

3008
03:34:48,790 --> 03:34:54,490
Marius, meanwhile, was grateful for finally
having the chance to help Thenardier, and

3009
03:34:54,490 --> 03:34:57,840
therefore to keep the promise he had made
to his father.

3010
03:34:57,840 --> 03:35:03,410
Thenardier's presence, however, offered him
another opportunity; it gave him the chance

3011
03:35:03,410 --> 03:35:07,080
to solve the mystery of Cosette's fortune.

3012
03:35:07,080 --> 03:35:09,180
'Thenardier,' he said.

3013
03:35:09,180 --> 03:35:14,930
'Shall I tell you the secret that you were
planning to sell me?

3014
03:35:14,930 --> 03:35:21,830
I, too, have sources of information, and probably
know more about the subject than you do.

3015
03:35:21,830 --> 03:35:27,370
Jean Valjean, as you say, is a murderer and
a thief.

3016
03:35:27,370 --> 03:35:34,720
He's a thief because he robbed a wealthy manufacturer
and mayor of Montreuil, M. Madeleine.

3017
03:35:34,720 --> 03:35:41,350
Jean Valjean, who knew the mayor's background,
reported him to the police and took advantage

3018
03:35:41,350 --> 03:35:46,939
of his arrest to take over half a million
francs from his Paris bank.

3019
03:35:46,939 --> 03:35:50,609
The manager of the bank told me this himself.

3020
03:35:50,609 --> 03:35:53,620
And he murdered the policeman, Javert.

3021
03:35:53,620 --> 03:35:57,930
I know this because I was there at the time.'

3022
03:35:57,930 --> 03:36:05,319
Thenardier looked puzzled for a moment, then
said, 'Monsieur, I think you are mistaken.'

3023
03:36:05,319 --> 03:36:07,949
'What!

3024
03:36:07,949 --> 03:36:09,609
Are you denying what I said?

3025
03:36:09,609 --> 03:36:11,370
Those are facts!'

3026
03:36:11,370 --> 03:36:16,670
'They are incorrect, and I do not like to
hear a man unjustly accused.

3027
03:36:16,670 --> 03:36:23,110
Jean Valjean did not rob M. Madeleine, nor
did he kill Javert.'

3028
03:36:23,110 --> 03:36:25,180
'How do you know?'

3029
03:36:25,180 --> 03:36:32,229
'First, he did not kill M. Madeleine because
he was M. Madeleine!

3030
03:36:32,229 --> 03:36:37,601
And second, he did not kill Javert because
Javert killed himself.

3031
03:36:37,601 --> 03:36:41,319
He killed himself by jumping into the river.'

3032
03:36:41,319 --> 03:36:44,690
'What proof do you have?'

3033
03:36:44,690 --> 03:36:47,270
Marius said, wide-eyed with disbelief.

3034
03:36:47,270 --> 03:36:53,960
'I have all the proof here,' Thenardier said,
producing an envelope in which there were

3035
03:36:53,960 --> 03:36:56,680
several documents and newspaper articles.

3036
03:36:56,680 --> 03:37:03,120
'I've spent a long time discovering the truth
about Jean Valjean.'

3037
03:37:03,120 --> 03:37:08,850
Marius studied the documents carefully, then
looked up with a smile of joy.

3038
03:37:08,850 --> 03:37:12,370
'But he's a splendid man!

3039
03:37:12,370 --> 03:37:18,540
The fortune was really his, and he's not a
murderer or thief at all!

3040
03:37:18,540 --> 03:37:22,060
He's a hero and a saint!'

3041
03:37:22,060 --> 03:37:27,210
'He's a thief and a murderer,'Thenardier said
quietly.

3042
03:37:27,210 --> 03:37:29,580
'What do you mean?'

3043
03:37:29,580 --> 03:37:36,910
'I told you that I do not like to see a man
accused unjustly, but I do like to see a man

3044
03:37:36,910 --> 03:37:39,320
punished for crimes he has committed.'

3045
03:37:39,320 --> 03:37:43,530
'And what crimes are those?'

3046
03:37:43,530 --> 03:37:49,100
Thenardier sat down and told Marius about
the time he had helped Valjean to escape from

3047
03:37:49,100 --> 03:37:50,699
the Paris sewer.

3048
03:37:50,699 --> 03:37:55,280
'He was carrying the body of a man he had
robbed and killed,' Thenardier said.

3049
03:37:55,280 --> 03:38:01,021
'Look, I have a piece of cloth from the dead
man's coat as proof.'

3050
03:38:01,021 --> 03:38:08,220
He produced a muddy piece of cloth and showed
it to Marius, who immediately went pale and

3051
03:38:08,220 --> 03:38:10,810
rose unsteadily to his feet.

3052
03:38:10,810 --> 03:38:18,160
As Thenardier continued to talk, Marius opened
a cupboard door and took out a coat.

3053
03:38:18,160 --> 03:38:21,239
'That man was me!'

3054
03:38:21,239 --> 03:38:22,590
Marius cried.

3055
03:38:22,590 --> 03:38:25,880
'And here is the coat I was wearing!'

3056
03:38:25,880 --> 03:38:32,660
Thenardier stared at the coat and the cloth
in his hands, speechless with fear.

3057
03:38:32,660 --> 03:38:38,060
He was even more surprised when, instead of
chasing him out of the room, Marius ran towards

3058
03:38:38,060 --> 03:38:42,939
him and pressed several thousand-franc notes
into his hand.

3059
03:38:42,939 --> 03:38:46,510
'You're a terrible man,' Marius said.

3060
03:38:46,510 --> 03:38:48,590
'A thief and a liar.

3061
03:38:48,590 --> 03:38:53,550
You came here to destroy a man, but you have
done the opposite.

3062
03:38:53,550 --> 03:38:58,910
If you hadn't saved my father's life at Waterloo,
I'd report you to the police.

3063
03:38:58,910 --> 03:39:05,540
I know that your wife is dead, but take the
money and start a new life in America with

3064
03:39:05,540 --> 03:39:07,540
your daughter.

3065
03:39:07,540 --> 03:39:11,760
When you arrive there, I'll send you another
20,000 francs.

3066
03:39:11,760 --> 03:39:14,250
Now get out.

3067
03:39:14,250 --> 03:39:18,080
I never want to see you again!'

3068
03:39:18,080 --> 03:39:26,779
When Thenardier had left, unable to believe
his good fortune, Marius ran to find Cosette

3069
03:39:26,779 --> 03:39:29,310
and told her everything immediately.

3070
03:39:29,310 --> 03:39:33,340
'We must go to him at once,' Marius said.

3071
03:39:33,340 --> 03:39:35,720
'He was the man who saved my life.

3072
03:39:35,720 --> 03:39:39,260
We must waste no time!'

3073
03:39:39,260 --> 03:39:48,500
Minutes later, he and Cosette were travelling
in a carriage to Number 7, rue de l'Homme-Arme.

3074
03:39:48,500 --> 03:39:49,500
***

3075
03:39:49,500 --> 03:39:55,600
Jean Valjean looked up when he heard the knock
on his door and called in a weak voice, 'Come

3076
03:39:55,600 --> 03:39:56,750
in.'

3077
03:39:56,750 --> 03:40:01,189
The door opened and Marius and Cosette appeared.

3078
03:40:01,189 --> 03:40:04,899
Cosette rushed to the chair where Jean Valjean
was sitting.

3079
03:40:04,899 --> 03:40:06,010
'Father!'

3080
03:40:06,010 --> 03:40:09,420
she cried, falling into his arms.

3081
03:40:09,420 --> 03:40:12,500
'So you've forgiven me?'

3082
03:40:12,500 --> 03:40:18,109
Valjean whispered, hugging Cosette to him
and turning to Marius.

3083
03:40:18,109 --> 03:40:22,229
'Cosette, did you hear what he said?'

3084
03:40:22,229 --> 03:40:26,820
Marius cried, tears of shame and guilt rolling
down his cheeks.

3085
03:40:26,820 --> 03:40:31,100
'He asked me to forgive him.

3086
03:40:31,100 --> 03:40:32,859
And do you know what he did?

3087
03:40:32,859 --> 03:40:36,820
He saved my life and he brought me back to
you.

3088
03:40:36,820 --> 03:40:40,890
He came to the barricade to save me, just
as he saved Javert.

3089
03:40:40,890 --> 03:40:45,859
He carried me on his back through the sewers
of Paris, to bring me to you.

3090
03:40:45,859 --> 03:40:51,950
Oh Cosette, I feel so ashamed of the way I've
treated him!'

3091
03:40:51,950 --> 03:40:57,250
'You have no need to say all this,' Valjean
murmured.

3092
03:40:57,250 --> 03:41:00,300
'Why didn't you say it yourself?'

3093
03:41:00,300 --> 03:41:01,300
Marius demanded.

3094
03:41:01,300 --> 03:41:07,040
'Why didn't you tell me that you were M. Madeleine
and that you saved Javert's life at the barricade?

3095
03:41:07,040 --> 03:41:11,080
Why didn't you tell me that I owed you my
life?'

3096
03:41:11,080 --> 03:41:17,120
'Because I thought it would be better to break
away.

3097
03:41:17,120 --> 03:41:23,189
If you had known the truth, you would have
felt obliged to be good to me, a worthless

3098
03:41:23,189 --> 03:41:24,189
criminal.

3099
03:41:24,189 --> 03:41:26,450
That would have upset everything.'

3100
03:41:26,450 --> 03:41:30,449
'What or whom would it have upset?'

3101
03:41:30,449 --> 03:41:31,449
Marius said.

3102
03:41:31,449 --> 03:41:34,460
'Well, we're not going to allow you to stay
here on your own.

3103
03:41:34,460 --> 03:41:37,070
You're going to come home with us.

3104
03:41:37,070 --> 03:41:40,220
You're Cosette's father and mine.

3105
03:41:40,220 --> 03:41:42,430
I won't allow you to spend another day here.'

3106
03:41:42,430 --> 03:41:50,170
'And you can't refuse this time,' Cosette
agreed, sitting on Jean Valjean's lap and

3107
03:41:50,170 --> 03:41:51,590
kissing his forehead.

3108
03:41:51,590 --> 03:41:54,420
'There's a carriage waiting for you.

3109
03:41:54,420 --> 03:41:58,909
I'm kidnapping you - by force, if necessary!'

3110
03:41:58,909 --> 03:42:04,420
Jean Valjean listened as she described the
view from the room that would be his, the

3111
03:42:04,420 --> 03:42:09,660
beauty of the garden, the singing of the birds,
but he was listening more to the music of

3112
03:42:09,660 --> 03:42:12,680
her voice than to the meaning of her words.

3113
03:42:12,680 --> 03:42:19,430
Finally, he said, 'Yes, it would be delightful,
but

3114
03:42:19,430 --> 03:42:25,000
Cosette, frightened, took his two hands in
hers.

3115
03:42:25,000 --> 03:42:28,250
'Your hands are so cold,' she said.

3116
03:42:28,250 --> 03:42:29,319
'Are you ill?

3117
03:42:29,319 --> 03:42:31,310
Are you in pain?'

3118
03:42:31,310 --> 03:42:34,489
'No,' said Valjean.

3119
03:42:34,489 --> 03:42:36,460
'I'm not in pain.

3120
03:42:36,460 --> 03:42:37,899
But

3121
03:42:37,899 --> 03:42:39,850
'But what?'

3122
03:42:39,850 --> 03:42:42,210
'I'm going to die soon.'

3123
03:42:42,210 --> 03:42:44,659
'Father, no!'

3124
03:42:44,659 --> 03:42:45,659
Cosette cried.

3125
03:42:45,659 --> 03:42:46,870
'You're going to live!

3126
03:42:46,870 --> 03:42:50,650
You must live, do you understand?'

3127
03:42:50,650 --> 03:42:55,500
Marius and Cosette both did their best to
raise Valjean's spirits, to show him how much

3128
03:42:55,500 --> 03:43:01,939
they loved and needed him, to fill him with
the strength and the desire to live again.

3129
03:43:01,939 --> 03:43:04,040
But it was too late.

3130
03:43:04,040 --> 03:43:10,020
Valjean smiled, his eyes shining with love
and happiness, but he was beginning to lose

3131
03:43:10,020 --> 03:43:11,020
strength.

3132
03:43:11,020 --> 03:43:15,180
'To die is nothing,' he murmured.

3133
03:43:15,180 --> 03:43:19,960
'But it is terrible not to live.'

3134
03:43:19,960 --> 03:43:26,989
Then, taking Cosette's sleeve and pressing
it to his lips, he said, 'Come close to me,

3135
03:43:26,989 --> 03:43:29,300
both of you.

3136
03:43:29,300 --> 03:43:32,370
I love you dearly.

3137
03:43:32,370 --> 03:43:36,800
How sweet it is to die like this.

3138
03:43:36,800 --> 03:43:40,120
And you love me too, dear Cosette.

3139
03:43:40,120 --> 03:43:45,920
You'll feel some grief for me, but not too
much.

3140
03:43:45,920 --> 03:43:49,949
I want you to have no great sorrows.

3141
03:43:49,949 --> 03:43:54,080
You must enjoy life, my children.

3142
03:43:54,080 --> 03:43:58,740
I'm leaving the two candlesticks by the bed
to Cosette.

3143
03:43:58,740 --> 03:44:06,760
They're made of silver, but to me they are
pure gold.

3144
03:44:06,760 --> 03:44:12,800
I don't know whether the person who gave them
to me is pleased as he looks down on me from

3145
03:44:12,800 --> 03:44:15,080
above.

3146
03:44:15,080 --> 03:44:17,659
I've done my best.

3147
03:44:17,659 --> 03:44:27,620
You mustn't forget, my children, that, despite
my money, I am one of the poor.'

3148
03:44:27,620 --> 03:44:33,550
As he spoke, Valjean's breathing became more
painful and he had difficulty moving his arms.

3149
03:44:33,550 --> 03:44:40,500
But as the weakness of his body increased,
his spirit grew in strength.

3150
03:44:40,500 --> 03:44:44,930
The light of an unknown world was shining
brightly in his eyes.

3151
03:44:44,930 --> 03:44:55,330
'Now, Cosette,' he breathed softly, 'the time
has come for me to tell you your mother's

3152
03:44:55,330 --> 03:44:57,130
name.

3153
03:44:57,130 --> 03:45:00,920
It was Fantine.

3154
03:45:00,920 --> 03:45:03,550
You must not forget it.

3155
03:45:03,550 --> 03:45:09,710
Your mother loved you greatly and she suffered
greatly.

3156
03:45:09,710 --> 03:45:14,790
She was as rich in sorrow as you are in happiness.

3157
03:45:14,790 --> 03:45:18,790
That is how God balances things out.

3158
03:45:18,790 --> 03:45:27,189
He watches us all from above and knows what
he is doing among his splendid stars.

3159
03:45:27,189 --> 03:45:33,989
And now I must leave you, my children.

3160
03:45:33,989 --> 03:45:37,030
Love one another always.

3161
03:45:37,030 --> 03:45:48,060
There is nothing else that matters in this
world except love.'

3162
03:45:48,060 --> 03:45:54,370
Cosette and Marius fell to their knees on
either side of him, holding back their tears.

3163
03:45:54,370 --> 03:46:00,570
Jean Valjean's hands rested on their bowed
heads, and did not move again.

3164
03:46:00,570 --> 03:46:08,939
He lay back with his head turned to the sky,
the light from the two silver candlesticks

3165
03:46:08,939 --> 03:46:09,690
falling on his smiling, peaceful face.

